{[%evp 0,23,19,29,23,-8,7,-19,0,0,-5,14,12,-15,29,33,21,33,32,25,15,31,37,29,
33,16]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 {Despite its modest appearances, the Reti opening
should not be underestimated. It provides White with flexibility and
positional soundness while avoiding long and forced opening variations that we
see in many 1.e4 and 1.d4 openings. The anti-Reti repertoire that I will
suggest here for Black is based on the super-solid Slav setup that usually  
(but as we shall see, not always) involves a combination of moves Bg4, d5, c6
and e6. Bishop's development to g4 - the so-called Capablanca System - is the
cornerstone of this repertoire. It is also possible to develop the bishop to
f5 (Lasker system), but this leads to slightly different positions where the
bishop often gets hit with an e2-e4 with a tempo, so it will not be examined
here. For the start, I would like to present a brief outline of the Capablanca
system against the Reti opening. Afterwards, we will discuss particular
opening variations in more detail.} Bg4 {Black has several move orders to
achieve the Capablanca system, including starting with 2...Nf6 and 2...c6, but
I prefer the immediate development of the bishop in the reversed Trompowsky
attack style, in order to preserve some flexibility (more on them later).} 3.
Bg2 ({White rarely plays} 3. Ne5 {which is a standard move in the Trompowsky
attack with colores reversed. It is important to remember that the bishop
retreats to} Bf5 {and in the case of} 4. c4 {we have} f6 $1 {, just like in
the main line of the Trompowsky! This is one of the reasons why I suggest
keeping the knight on g8 for the time being.}) 3... e6 $5 {This unusual move
order has been gaining popularity among strong GMs recently. The Reti opening,
just like the Italian game, is full of move order subtleties, so I believe
that we should strive for the best/most flexible move order with Black. The
main point behind it is that we reserve the option of developing the queenside
with ...c5, ... Nc6 should White choose to play the King's Indian attack (with
Nbd2 and e2-e4) instead of the Reti opening with c2-c4. This is a good moment
to enumerate White's four most typical approaches when playing 1.Nf3 d5 2.g3:
1. The Reti approach: White plays c2-c4 with d2-d3 2. The Catalan approach:
White plays c2-c4 with d2-d4 3. The King's Indian Attack (KIA) approach: White
plays d2-d3 with e2-e4 4. Double fianchetto approach: White plays b2-b3,
usually in a combination with c2-c4 and d2-d3. Having these approaches in mind,
it will be easier to discuss differences between the 'classical' move order
with 3...c6 and the 'modern' one with 3...e6.} ({The classical move order is:} 
3... c6 4. O-O Nf6 {Let us examine Black's responses to White's 4 typical
approaches from the list above.} 5. d3 ({If White goes for the Catalan
approach:} 5. h3 Bh5 6. c4 e6 7. d4 {then we transpose directly into the
Catalan approach after 3...e6. So, there is no difference between the two move
orders if White decides to go for this variation.}) ({The double fianchetto
approach} 5. b3 Nbd7 6. Bb2 {also transposes to 3...e6 move order after} e6 {
etc. The differences between the two move orders become obvious if White goes
for either the KIA approach or the Reti approach.}) 5... Nbd7 {Now White can
choose between the Reti approach:} 6. c4 ({and the KIA approach with} 6. Nbd2 {
The key difference compared to 3...e6 move order is that Black can play} e5 {
here. After} 7. e4 {we get a very popular position for this opening, that will
be examined in the game 3.2) Even though 7...dxe4 is the most popular move, I
would suggest that we keep tension in the centre with} Be7 (7... dxe4 8. dxe4
Bc5 {is the main line, but White has a fairly easy play here.}) 8. h3 Bh5 9.
Qe1 {and now Black has an enterprising 'Marshall-attack' type of sacrifice at
his disposal:} O-O $1 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. g4 Bg6 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. Qxe5 Bd6 $44)
({The alternative move order that White sometimes employs to push e2-e4 is} 6.
Qe1 e5 7. e4 {when I would still suggest keeping central tension, although
with a different bishop move:} Bd6 $5 8. h3 Bh5 9. Nh4 {and, once again, Black
can offer an ambitious pawn sacrifice in order to speed up his development:}
O-O $1 10. g4 Bg6 11. Nxg6 fxg6 $5 12. g5 Nh5 13. exd5 cxd5 14. Bxd5+ Kh8 $132)
6... e6 {Now White typically play} 7. cxd5 {using the fact that black knight
has already been developed to d7 so that neither 7...cxd5 nor 7...Bxf3 are not
attractive for Black anymore. The key difference here compared to 3...e6
system is that in the latter, we keep the knight on b8, which takes some sting
out of the cxd5 exchange.} exd5 (7... Bxf3 $2 {is our preferred choice in 3...
e6 move order, but it doesn't work here tactically because of the intermezzo}
8. dxe6 $1 Bxg2 9. exd7+ Qxd7 10. Kxg2 $18) (7... cxd5 {on the other hand,
gives White an initiative in the endgame after} 8. Qb3 Nc5 9. Qb5+ Qd7 10. Nc3
{etc.}) {Now we have an imbalanced pawn structure, which leads to rich
middlegames with chances for both sides. Below are some of the key variations
that will be examined in a separate file (1.2) Reti approach - classical way).}
8. Nc3 (8. h3 Bxf3 9. Bxf3 (9. exf3 $5 Be7 10. Nd2 O-O 11. f4) 9... Bc5) 8...
Bc5 (8... Be7 $5 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Bxf3 d4) 9. Qb3 Bb6 10. Na4 O-O 11. Nxb6 axb6)
4. O-O ({Once again, White can win a tempo with} 4. Ne5 {but this time around,
it is important to remember that the bishop retreats to} Bh5 {Differences
between this and 4...Bf5 will be explained in the next game, 1.1).}) 4... Nf6 {
Just as we did with the classical 3...c6, let us now examine what to play
against each of White's four typical approaches. These days, the most popular
approach for White is the Catalan one with} 5. h3 ({The main point besides the
modern 3...e6 move order can be seen if White chooses the KIA approach here:} 
5. d3 Be7 6. Nbd2 {Now we can safely continue} c5 $5 {(since White hasn't put
any pressure on our center with c2-c4) and after} 7. e4 Nc6 8. h3 Bh5 {Black
gets a good version of the reversed Torre attack where he is down a tempo, but
that doesn't really matter much in this closed position. We will examine it in
the game 3.1)}) ({In case of the Reti approach} 5. c4 {, we play} c6 {and now
White has two basic plans:} 6. cxd5 ({and} 6. d3 Be7 7. Qb3 {when we are ready
to play a solid endgame after:} Qb6 8. Be3 Qxb3 9. axb3 a6 {etc.}) ({Finally,
there is also the double fianchetto approach, perhaps the least critical of
White's four approaches (examined in game 4)). Black usually gets a
comfortable position by playing} 6. b3 Nbd7 7. Bb2 Bd6 8. d3 O-O 9. Nbd2 a5 10.
a3 Re8 {preparing ...e6-e5 break. This approach works better for White when
the black bishop is on f5.}) {Now, it is important to remember the intermezzo}
6... Bxf3 $1 ({The main point of eliminating the f3-knight can be seen in the
variation:} 6... cxd5 7. Qb3 Qd7 8. Ne5) 7. Bxf3 {which allows us to safely
recapture on d5 with the c-pawn:} cxd5 {and Black has a super-solid position
where he will develop the knight to the active c6-square. White usually
continues} 8. d4 (8. Qb3 {is now safely met by} Qd7) 8... Nc6 9. Nc3 Be7 {
when we have a Catalan type of position which offers chances for both sides in
the long run.}) 5... Bh5 6. c4 c6 7. d4 {White has achieved a Catalan setup,
the only difference being that the bishop is not on c8, but h5. In principle,
this detail should be in Black's favour, but things are not so simple. White
inserted h2-h3 in order to sideline the bishop so that he could either win the
bishop pair with g3-g4, Ne5/Nh4-Nxg6; or even try to trap it with g3-g4, f2-f4
etc. in some lines. A solid body of opening theory has developed in this
system over the last 5-6 years and we will examine it in the game 2). Let us
quickly run through the main variations:} Nbd7 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Nh4 $5 (9. Qb3
Qb6 10. Qe3+ {used to be the main line, when White typically wins the bishop
pair after} Be7 11. Nh4 Bg6 12. Nc3 {etc.}) (9. Ne5 {is a modern sharp option
that is best met by} Ne4 $1) 9... Bg6 10. Nc3 Be7 {and here White has a choice
between the positional variation} 11. Nxg6 ({and sharper} 11. f3 {preparing 12.
e4, when Black has a surprising solution:} Qc7 12. Bf4 Qb6 $1 13. Na4 Qd8 $1 {
with complicated play.}) 11... hxg6 12. h4 {that leads into Slav type of
positions.} *

