1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Bg4 3. Bg2 (3. Ne5 Bf5 {This is more accurate} ({than} 3... Bh5
{because of} 4. g4 $1 {and White has a slight initiative in all variations:}
Bg6 (4... f6 5. gxh5 fxe5 6. c4) 5. h4) 4. c4 {The most principled
continuation. It is important to note that in case of 4.g3, Black could simply
retreat the bishop to c8, which was not an option in 3...Bh5 line.} (4. d4 {
is rather harmless for Black since after} c6 5. c4 e6 6. Bg2 Nd7 7. O-O Ngf6 {
his bishop is placed better on f5 than the usual h5, as it controls the
important b1-h7 diagonal.} 8. Nc3 Be7 9. Qb3 Qb6 $11) 4... f6 $1 {Black plays
the same way in the Trompowsky attack with colours reversed, thereby expelling
the knight from the central square and preparing to push ...e7-e5.} (4... Nd7 {
gives White some initiative:} 5. d4 Ngf6 6. Bg2 e6 7. Qb3 $36) 5. Nf3 (5. Qa4+
c6 6. Nf3 d4 $13 {is another line that is similar to the Trompowsky.}) 5...
dxc4 6. Na3 e5 7. Nxc4 Be6 8. Ne3 Nc6 9. d3 Bc5 10. Bg2 Nge7 11. O-O Qd7 $15 {
0-1 (26) Stuemer, P (2155)-Slobodjan, R (2575) Fuerth 1998}) 3... e6 $5 {
In this game, we will examine this modern approach; in the next one, the
classical one with 3...c6.} 4. c4 ({Here, too, White can play} 4. Ne5 {when}
Bh5 {is a better choice} ({than} 4... Bf5 {With ...e7-e6 inserted, the bishop
doesn't have a retreat on the h3-c8 diagonal, which becomes apparent in the
line} 5. d3 f6 6. e4 $1 $14) 5. c4 ({Another important tactical detail to
remember is that} 5. g4 {doesn't work that well for White as a move ago since .
..e6 is a more useful move for him than Bg2 is for White. Thus, after} f6 $1 6.
gxh5 fxe5 7. c4 Nf6 $132 {Black has his fair share of chances in a complicated
position.} 8. Qb3 Nc6 $1 9. Qxb7 Nd4 $17) 5... Nd7 6. d4 c6 7. O-O Ngf6 {
Here, we almost have a transposition into the Catalan approach (game 2)), with
the only difference that White does not have h2-h3 here. However, even after}
8. Nc3 (8. h3 {is a direct transposition into the main line of game 2)}) {
we should follow the recommendation to take the knight} 8... Nxe5 $1 ({instead
of} 8... Be7 {when White can play} 9. f4 $1 O-O 10. h3 Bg6 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. g4
$14 {transposing into a position that we would like to avoid with Black, as
explained in game 2).}) 9. dxe5 Nd7 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. f4 ({The other plan is} 
11. h3 Bc5 12. g4 Bg6 13. e4 {when Black has a good reply in} d4 14. Na4 O-O
15. f4 Be7 $1 16. b3 (16. f5 b5 17. fxg6 hxg6 $17) 16... f6 $132) 11... Bc5+ {
The point behind Nxe5 is that we don't waste a developing tempo on Be7 so that
we can develop it to a more active square - c5.} 12. Kh1 O-O 13. h3 a6 14. Qe1
{1/2-1/2 (48) Gutman,L (2495)-Huebner,R (2625) Playchess.com INT 2003} f6 $1
$132 {Black should remember to play this move sooner or later in this
structure.} 15. exf6 Nxf6 16. e4 d4 17. e5 dxc3 18. exf6 Qxf6 19. bxc3 $11)
4... c6 5. O-O Nf6 {One of the main ideas for White in the Reti opening is to
determine the central pawn structure with} 6. cxd5 ({A more flexible plan is} 
6. d3 {when Black has as much as four good responses. My suggestion is to play}
Be7 (6... Nbd7 {is the 'classical' Reti, discussed in the next game 1.2)} 7.
cxd5 exd5) (6... Bd6 {is Carlsen's favorite}) (6... dxc4 {is another popular
option for Black, leading to a different pawn structure} 7. dxc4) 7. Qb3 ({Now
} 7. cxd5 Bxf3 8. Bxf3 cxd5 {is similar to the main line, only with d3 and Be7
inserted, which favors Black slightly. His position is very solid and sound,
for example:} 9. Nc3 Nc6 10. Bg2 O-O 11. Bd2 Rc8 12. Rc1 Qb6 13. Na4 Qa6 14. a3
Nd7 15. Nc3 b5 16. Kh1 Qb6 17. f4 a5 18. f5 b4 19. axb4 axb4 20. Na4 Qb5 21.
fxe6 fxe6 22. Bh3 Nd4 23. Rxc8 Rxc8 24. e3 Nf5 25. e4 dxe4 26. dxe4 Qc6 $11 {
1/2-1/2 (35) Mastrovasilis,A (2537)-Prohaszka,P (2554) Achaia 2012}) 7... Qb6
8. Be3 {This is White's big point - he forces the queen trade in order to
obtain an endgame with a slight space advantage and, quite often, a bishop
pair advantage.} Qxb3 9. axb3 a6 {However, Black is extremely solid here.
White usually continues} 10. h3 Bh5 11. g4 Bg6 12. Ne5 {to win the bishop pair}
Nbd7 13. Nxg6 hxg6 {and it is not easy for White to unlock Black's compact
pawn chain. On the other hand, Black is looking for ways to exploit White's
weaknesses on the dark squares and to neutralize his space advantage.} 14. Nc3
Bd6 ({I analyzed another interesting option for Black:} 14... Nh7 $5 $146 15.
f4 f5 $1 16. g5 (16. d4 Nhf6 17. g5 Ne4 18. Nxe4 dxe4 $11) 16... dxc4 $1 17.
bxc4 e5 $132 {which suddenly leads to very dynamic play.} 18. h4 Nhf8 19. Bf2
Ne6 20. fxe5 Nxe5 21. d4 Ng4 22. d5 $13) 15. f4 Ke7 {The king is best placed
in the centre, while the rook remains on the h-file, keeping an eye on the
h3-pawn.} 16. d4 Ne4 $1 17. Nxe4 {1/2-1/2 (17) Marin,M (2581)-Mastrovasilis,D 
(2607) Calimanesti 2014} dxe4 18. g5 f5 $11) ({It should be noted that} 6. Qb3
{is premature before Black has committed his bishop to e7-square. We can see
this point after} Qb6 7. d3 Nbd7 8. Be3 (8. Qc2 Bd6 9. Be3 Qc7 10. cxd5 exd5
11. Nc3 O-O 12. Bd4 Rfe8 $11) {when Black can play} 8... Bc5 $11 {in one go})
6... Bxf3 $1 {The key move of our preferred setup. Once the knight is
eliminated, there are no more unpleasant Nf3-e5 jumps and the white
light-squared bishop remains quite restricted behind f7-d5 pawn chain.} (6...
cxd5 {is less accurate in the view of} 7. Qb3 Qb6 (7... Qd7 $4 8. Ne5) 8. Qxb6
axb6 9. Nc3 $14) 7. Bxf3 cxd5 8. d4 {These days, this is the main plan for
White. He stabilizes the situation in the centre, achieving a Catalan pawn
structure, and usually prepares the e4-break.} (8. Qb3 Qd7) ({For} 8. d3 {
plan, see the game Mastrovasilis-Prohaszka above.}) 8... Nc6 9. e3 ({White can
also opt to play on the queenside. The following game is a good example of how
to neutralize this plan.} 9. Nc3 Be7 10. b3 O-O 11. Bb2 Qd7 12. e3 Rfc8 13. Qd3
Rc7 14. Rfc1 Rac8 15. Qe2 Qd8 16. Nb5 Rd7 17. Bg2 h6 18. Nc3 Qa5 19. Qb5 Qd8
20. Na4 a6 21. Qf1 Bd6 22. Rc2 Rdc7 23. Rac1 Nd7 {Black has a super-solid
position. White's bishop pair advantage is only a nominal one since his
bishops are inactive.} 24. a3 Na5 25. Qd3 Rxc2 26. Rxc2 Rxc2 27. Qxc2 Qc7 $11 {
0-1 (62) Gabuzyan,H (2557)-Meier,G (2621) Chess.com INT 2020}) 9... Be7 {
The bishop is better here than on d6,} ({since} 9... Bd6 {blocks heavy pieces'
view to the important d-file. In addition, black knights can sometimes be
manoeuvred to a good d6-square, via e8/e4 or a5-c4.}) 10. Nc3 O-O 11. Qe2 Rc8
12. Rd1 Qd7 13. Bd2 Rfd8 {[#] Black is fully centralized, which makes it very
difficult for White to open the centre with the help of e3-e4. That said, he
can gradually prepare this pawn break with a series of manoeuvres, starting
with} 14. Be1 $5 {preparing to continue Bf3-g2, f2-f3, Be1-f2 and finally
e3-e4. In, what is a model game for this type of position, Magnus Carlsen
demonstrates an effective method of stopping this potentially dangerous plan:}
Ne8 15. Rac1 f5 $1 ({In case of something less prophylactic, such as:} 15...
Nd6 16. Bg2 Bf8 17. f3 g6 18. Bf2 Bg7 {White pushes} 19. e4 {and obtains an
advantage in the centre.} dxe4 20. fxe4 e5 21. dxe5 Bxe5 22. Nd5 $14) 16. Bg2
Nf6 17. Na4 ({It is crucial to understand that in the case of} 17. f3 {[#]
Black would be just in time to undermine the e3-e4 plan with} g5 $1 18. Bf2 g4
$132) 17... b6 18. Nc3 ({Perhaps White should have switched his attention to
the queenside instead} 18. Qb5 g5 19. Nc3 g4 20. Bf1 Kf7 21. Qa4 {although
Black is perfectly fine after} Nb8 $1 22. Qxd7 (22. Bb5 Qb7) 22... Rxd7 23. h3
h5 24. Kg2 Rdc7 $11) 18... Na5 (18... g5 $5) 19. Nb1 (19. Qa6 $142 Nc4 20. b3
Nd6 21. a4 $1 $132) 19... Nc4 20. Rc2 {White's play over the last couple of
moves was quite tentative and Carlsen takes the initiative with} g5 $1 21. Rdc1
g4 {Now White's kingside structure has been frozen, but Black has some other
ideas in mind, as we will see.} 22. Bf1 Ne4 $11 {A picture-perfect strategy by
the World Champion.} 23. b3 Ncd6 24. Qa6 Rxc2 25. Rxc2 Kf7 $1 {In a position
where most people would trade the heavy pieces on the c-file, Carlsen plays
much more ambitiously, preparing the attack on the h-file. With the last move,
he cleared the 8th rank for the rook to join the attack.} 26. a4 h5 $36 27. a5
Rb8 28. axb6 Rxb6 29. Qa2 Qb7 $19 {0-1 (35) Rapport,R (2747)-Carlsen,M (2882)
Saint Louis 2019} *

