1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Bg4 3. Bg2 c6 {This is the 'classical' move order to reach the
Reti-Slav with Bg4.} 4. c4 ({The most accurate move order for White is} 4. O-O
Nf6 5. d3 {not revealing his intentions (KIA and Reti are still both possible),
so that after} Nbd7 ({In the case of} 5... e6 {White could get a slightly
improved version of the KIA with:} 6. h3 Bh5 7. Qe1 Be7 8. e4 O-O 9. Nc3 {
which is still playable for Black, of course.}) 6. c4 ({Alternatively,} 6. Nbd2
e5 7. e4 {transposes to the classical variation of the KIA (game 3.2)).}) 6...
e6 {we transpose into the main line here.}) 4... e6 5. O-O Nf6 6. d3 Nbd7 ({
Black could play} 6... Be7 {transposing to the game 1.1) but in the case of 4.
0-0 Nf6 5.d3 move order, he would not have this option.}) 7. cxd5 {Now 7...
Bxf3 doesn't work for tactical reasons, so Black's best option is} exd5 8. Nc3
({White might also insert} 8. h3 {when I would suggest taking on f3} Bxf3 ({
in the view of} 8... Bh5 9. e4 $1 dxe4 10. dxe4 Bc5 11. Qc2 O-O 12. Nh4 $14) 9.
Bxf3 (9. exf3 $5 {looks anti-positional, but it has more positional venom than
it might seem at the first glance. White's pawn structure is worse, but the
upside is that he will control the centre very well, taking away good outposts
from black pieces after f3-f4 move.} Be7 10. f4 O-O 11. Nd2 Re8 12. Nf3 Bf8 13.
Be3 ({I believe that Kryvoruchko's plan} 13. Qc2 $5 Bc5 14. Bd2 a5 15. Bc3 {
is better.}) 13... Bc5 $5 {which was a funny bishop dance to provoke} 14. d4 $6
{White was better off retreating to d2 since now Black gains an outpost on e4.}
Bb6 15. Ne5 Ne4 $11 {Black is already fine and soon I obtained a more
promising position thanks to a couple of nice knight manoeuvres.} 16. Qf3 Nd6
17. h4 f6 18. Ng4 Nf5 19. Rad1 Nf8 $1 20. Rd3 Ne6 21. Rfd1 Nc7 $1 22. Nh2 Nb5
23. h5 Qe7 24. Qg4 Nbd6 $15 {1/2-1/2 (58) Dizdarevic,E (2502)-Kuljasevic,D  
(2561) Zadar 2012}) 9... Bc5 10. e3 O-O 11. a3 a5 12. b3 {Kuljasevic, Davorin:
'White remains flexible with his pawn structure and banks on his bishop pair
advantage in the long run. This sounds as good an opening outcome for White in
the Reti opening as it gets (and I also have unpleasant memories of getting
outplayed on the black side of this system by Laurent Fressinet once), though
I don't believe that Black is objectively worse just yet.'} Bd6 (12... Ne8 $5
13. Bg2 Nd6 {[%csl Gd6,Ye4][%cal Yd6b5,Yd6f5]} 14. Ra2 (14. Bb2 $5 Re8 15. Nd2
Bb6 16. Qc2 Qg5 17. Nf3 Qg6 18. Rfc1 Re7 $132 {[%csl Re3,Rg3][%cal Ga8e8]})
14... Re8 15. Re2 Re6 16. Bb2 Qe7 17. Rfe1 Re8 18. Qd2 Bb6 19. Nc3 Nf5 20. d4
h5 21. Na4 Bc7 $132 {0-1 Grachev,B (2659)-Shirov,A (2702)/Loo 2014/CBM 160 (43)
}) 13. Bg2 Re8 (13... Nc5 14. Bb2 a4 15. b4 Nb3 16. Ra2 Re8 17. Nd2 Nxd2 18.
Qxd2 $14) 14. Nd2 Nc5 (14... Qb6 $142 {[%csl Rb3,Gb6,Rd3,Re3] Kuljasevic,
Davorin: '<=>!?' Kuljasevic, Davorin: 'putting pressure on white pawns,
deserved serious attention.'} 15. Qc2 (15. Rb1 Nc5 16. Qc2 Qa6 {[%csl Rd3]} 17.
d4 Nd3 $132 (17... Nce4 $132)) (15. Bb2 Be5 16. d4 Bd6 $11) 15... Qc5 $5 (15...
Rxe3 16. Nc4 $1 (16. fxe3 Qxe3+ 17. Rf2 (17. Kh1 Nh5 $36) 17... Bxg3 $36) 16...
dxc4 17. Bxe3 cxb3 18. Bxb6 bxc2 19. Be3 $14) (15... Be5 16. Rb1) (15... Nc5
16. Bb2 Nfd7 17. Rfe1 Qb5 18. Bf1 Ne6 19. Rac1 $14) (15... Rad8 16. Nf3 (16.
Bb2 Rxe3 $1) (16. Rb1 Qc5 17. Qd1 Qb5 18. d4 (18. Nf3 Nc5) 18... Nf8 $11) 16...
Ne5 (16... Qc5 17. Qb1 Qb6 18. Bb2) 17. Bb2 (17. Nd4 c5 18. Nf5 Bf8 19. Bb2 d4
$1 $132) 17... Nxf3+ 18. Bxf3 Be5 19. Bxe5 Rxe5 20. d4 Re7 21. b4 axb4 22. Rab1
$14) 16. Qb1 Qb6 {[%csl Ra1,Rb1]} 17. Re1 {[%csl Re3]} (17. Bb2 Rxe3 $1) (17.
