his dark squares could become more vulnerable in the long run.}) 10. Nc3 Be7 {
[#] Now, White has several directions:} 11. Nxg6 {is the most straightforward,
when he gets the bishop pair advantage, similar to 9.Qb3 line.} (11. f3 $5 {
However, is the most challenging move. White prepares to build a strong pawn
centre with 12.e4. Black can easily get into a worse position if he is not
well-prepared for this line. His best reply is the surprising queen manoeuvre :
} Qc7 $1 (11... c5 12. Be3 $1 $14) (11... O-O $6 12. e4 Nh5 13. Nxg6 hxg6 14.
Ne2 $14) 12. Bf4 {[#]} Qb6 {'!' This already looks a bit strange, but the
engine has a 'cunning plan'.} ({A much more human continuation is} 12... Bd6 {
though this does not suffice for the equality after} 13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. Kh2 Nh5
15. Qe1 $1 {and White pushes e2-e4 on the next move, with an advantage.}) 13.
Na4 Qd8 $1 {[%csl Ra4,Rf4] [#] A stunning concept - I could not believe it at
first. If you compare this position to the one on the previous diagram (after
11.f3), you will realize that black pieces are in the same exact positions
where they were, while White has developed his bishop to f4, moved his knight
to a4, and has an extra move to boot. In essence, with this weird queen
manoeuvring, Black has granted his opponent 3 full tempi! How in the world can
this solve Black's initial problem with the e2-e4 break? Moreover, isn't such
play just plain stupid and why would the engine claim that it is good for
Black? Like I said, I had a difficult time believing in this concept not only
the first but also the next few times when I analyzed this position. However,
the more I looked at it, the more it transpired that this counterintuitive
sequence actually makes sense. While White pieces are more actively placed
than 3 moves ago, the bishop on f4 is somewhat exposed to attacks and the
knight on a4 is actually placed worse on the rim than on c3 when it comes to
executing the e2-e4 break. As for the extra tempo - well, what is the use of
it if you need to spend it for something that is not 14.e4?} 14. g4 {Logically,
White defends against 14.. .Nh5 and prepares 15.e4. Now, Black has a strong
counter-idea:} Nf8 {'!'} 15. e4 {'!' This is the critical continuation - if
this works, White is just better.} (15. Bg3 $2 {fails to} Nxg4 $1 16. Nxg6 Ne3
{This intermezzo is the point.} 17. Qc1 Nxf1 18. Nxh8 Nxg3 $19) ({White could
also try to put his sidelined knight to use with} 15. Nc5 {though after} b6 16.
Nb3 Ne6 17. Be5 Nd7 18. Nxg6 hxg6 19. Bg3 O-O $13 {Black should be fine due to
White's dark-square weaknesses.}) 15... Ne6 (15... dxe4 {loses material after}
16. fxe4 Bxe4 17. g5 Bxg2 18. gxf6) 16. Be3 dxe4 ({It is tempting to win the
pawn with} 16... Nxg4 17. hxg4 Bxh4 {but after} 18. exd5 $1 cxd5 19. f4 f5 20.
Qb3 $36 {White has a strong initiative.}) 17. Nxg6 {[#] In this position,
almost everyone would automatically take on g6, but the engine points out
another outrageous resource; this time, a tactical one:} Nd5 $3 {What a move!
Now we enter a wild tactical sequence.} ({There is probably also nothing wrong
with} 17... hxg6 $5 18. fxe4 Qa5 19. Nc3 Rd8 20. e5 Nd5 21. Nxd5 cxd5 {when
Black has a solid enough position, but the text is much more enterprising.})
18. Nxh8 Nxe3 19. Nxf7 {'!' A strong intermezzo.} (19. Qd2 {'?' is worse than
it looks, in the view of} Nxf1 20. Rxf1 e3 $1 (20... Bf6 $17 {The extra knight
on h8 isn't going anywhere and meanwhile white pawn centre falls apart.}) 21.
Qxe3 Qxd4 22. Qxd4 Nxd4 $11) 19... Kxf7 20. fxe4+ Nxf1 21. Qxf1+ Kg8 {[#]
After the dust has settled, White can claim an extra pawn, but he has a couple
of positional problems, most notably his weak dark squares. Thus, Black has
full compensation for the pawn, as in the following lines:} 22. d5 (22. Rd1 Qd6
23. Qc4 Bf6 $1 $132) 22... cxd5 23. exd5 Ng5 $44 {followed by ...Qd8-d6-e5, ...
Be7-d6, etc.}) (11. f4 Be4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Nf5 O-O 14. Qb3 (14. Bxe4 dxe4 15.
d5 Bc5+ 16. Kg2 Qf6 17. dxc6 Nb6 $1 $11) 14... Rb8 15. g4 Nd6 16. Nxe7+ Qxe7
17. f5 Rfe8 18. Bf4 Nb6 $11 {1-0 (32) Donchenko,A (2604)-Pavasovic,D (2546)
chess.com INT 2019}) 11... hxg6 12. h4 $5 ({The alternative plan for White is
the minority attack:} 12. Rb1 O-O 13. b4 {but Black can stop it in its tracks
with} b5 $1 14. e4 dxe4 15. Nxe4 Nd5 $11) 12... O-O 13. Bf3 Re8 14. Kg2 {
White's idea is to prepare the h4-h5 break. Black should have sufficient
resources to neutralize it and to keep a strong presence in the centre.} Nb6
