{[%evp 0,26,28,30,20,-6,0,-2,10,-8,-1,0,9,-1,15,12,12,4,28,9,9,-5,-5,-36,-36,
-35,-33,-34,-34]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Bg4 3. Bg2 e6 $5 {This move order is
designed exactly against White's transposition from the Reti opening into the
King's Indian Attack.} 4. d3 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 {Black is not showing his cards
with the c-pawn yet. In the case of 6.c4, we would go 6...c6, but if White
prepares the e2-e4 move, it is possible to develop more actively, with ...c5, .
..Nc6.} 6. Nbd2 (6. Qe1 {is a clever alternative. White prepares e2-e4 and
unpins his f3-knight at the same time. Black needs to be careful now since Ne5
becomes an important option for White. Therefore, the prophylactic} Bh5 $5 {
leaves the best impression.} (6... c5 $6 {allows White to take the initiative
with} 7. Ne5 Bh5 8. e4 O-O 9. f4 $36) 7. e4 {Now, 7..c5?! transposes to the
note above, but Black can prevent White's plan with} Nc6 $5 {which seems like
a very stable setup against the KIA.} 8. Nbd2 (8. Nc3 O-O $11) (8. e5 $2 Nd7 9.
Bf4 g5 $19) 8... Nb4 $5 9. Qd1 c5 $132) 6... c5 7. e4 {Most people play like
this,} ({but White has another typical idea here:} 7. h3 Bh5 8. g4 Bg6 9. Ne5
Nbd7 10. Nxg6 hxg6 {Winning the bishop pair came with a price. The semi-open
h-file and weakened dark squares give Black serious counterplay.} 11. e4 (11.
e3 Qc7 12. Qe2 Ne5 $5 13. f4 Nc6 $13) 11... dxe4 12. dxe4 Ne5 $1 13. Qe2 g5 14.
Nc4 Nfd7 15. f4 Nxc4 16. Qxc4 O-O 17. e5 Nb6 18. Qe2 gxf4 19. Rd1 Qc7 20. Bxf4
c4 $1 $132 {1/2-1/2 (32) Ivanchuk,V (2710)-Lupulescu,C (2606) Batumi 2018}) (7.
Ne5 {is possible here, too, although the key difference compared to 6.Qe1
becomes obvious after} Bh5 {- there is no e2-e4.} 8. f4 Nbd7 $11) 7... Nc6 8.
h3 Bh5 9. Re1 ({Some players prefer to settle the pawn tension in the centre
at once by playing} 9. exd5 Nxd5 {but Black should not have any problems here;
the position is roughly balanced after the logical} 10. Nc4 Qc7 11. Re1 O-O 12.
g4 Bg6 13. Nce5 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Bd6 $11 {0-1 (33) Burovic,I (2322)-Marjanovic,D 
(2392) Bihac 2016}) 9... dxe4 $5 {This is World champion's choice, so we have
to consider it seriously.} ({There is, of course, nothing wrong with the simple
} 9... O-O {when it is difficult to suggest something better than} 10. exd5 (
10. c3 d4 $1) (10. e5 $6 Nd7 11. g4 Bg6 12. Nf1 b5 $15 {looks like a great KIA
for Black, with the bishop on g6.}) 10... Nxd5 11. g4 Bg6 12. Nc4 $11) 10. dxe4
O-O 11. e5 $6 {This move is usually not so good for White when the bishop pins
the f3-knight because the e5-pawn may become quite vulnerable.} (11. Qe2 Nd7
12. c3 {is a less commital plan, though Black is still quite happy about his
position after} Qc7 $13) 11... Nd7 (11... Nd5 $5 $15) 12. g4 Bg6 13. Nc4 Nb4
$36 {1-0 (49) Caruana,F (2808)-Carlsen,M (2832) Paris 2017} *

