1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Bg4 3. Bg2 c6 4. O-O Nd7 {This is the classical setup against
the KIA in the Bg4 Reti-Slav. Black is getting ready to meet White's e2-e4
with the symmetrical ...e7-e5.} 5. d3 Ngf6 6. Nbd2 ({As explained in the
previous game, White can also prepare e2-e4 with} 6. Qe1 e5 7. e4 {In this
case, the e5-pawn is hanging immediately, so I would suggest that we play} Bd6
$5 (7... dxe4 {is, once again, a safe option, but also the one that gives
White easier play. The following top-GM game is a good example:} 8. dxe4 Bd6 9.
Nbd2 O-O 10. h3 Bh5 11. Nc4 Bc7 12. a4 Re8 (12... b5 13. axb5 cxb5 14. Ne3 $14
{[%cal Ge3d5,Ge3f5]} Nxe4 15. Nh4 $1 $16) 13. Nh4 Nc5 14. Nf5 Ne6 15. Be3 Nf4
16. f3 $1 Nxg2 17. Kxg2 Bg6 18. Rd1 Nd5 19. Nh4 Nxe3+ 20. Qxe3 Qe7 21. Qb3 Rab8
22. Rf2 Red8 23. Rxd8+ Bxd8 24. Rd2 Bc7 25. Rd3 Qe6 26. Qb4 b6 27. b3 a6 28.
Qd2 b5 29. Rd7 $1 $36 {Kramnik,V (2801)-Vitiugov,N (2712)/Alekhine mem Paris/
St Petersburg/2013/}) 8. h3 Bh5 9. Nh4 O-O {This move is an implicit pawn
sacrifice, but the one that Black is ready for.} 10. g4 (10. Nf5 Bc5 11. Nc3
Bg6 $11 {is quite comfortable for Black. Note that the main difference
compared to Kramnik-Vitiugov above is that Black has kept the pawn on d5,
which gives him a space advantage compared to the symmetrical pawn structure
after ...dxe4 exchange.}) 10... Bg6 11. Nxg6 (11. Nf5 {is not at all good
because of} Bxf5 12. exf5 (12. gxf5 Re8 $15 {when Black has a very solid and
nice position.}) 12... h6 {preventing g5 for the time being.} 13. Qd1 Re8 14.
Re1 (14. h4 $2 Nh7 $17) 14... Qb6 $15 {Once again a very harmonious position
for Black.}) 11... fxg6 $5 $146 {This recapture is perhaps an improvement over
the game Kramnik-Sjugirov (11...hxg6). Black opens the f-file for counterplay
against White's weakened king shield.} (11... hxg6 12. g5 Nh5 13. exd5 cxd5 14.
Bxd5 Nf4 $44 {Sjugirov makes the most logical move. He attacks the d5 bishop
and also the g5-pawn forcing White to take the knight on f4.} 15. Bxf4 exf4 16.
h4 {These kingside pawns might look weak but one important fact to understand
here is that Black would like to break this structure with f6 at some point
but with the bishop so strongly placed on d5, it is simply impossible. My
chess sense tells me that Black should definitely have compensation here but
Kramnik's subsequent play casts doubt on it.} Qc8 {Openly eyeing the c2-pawn
and in a stealthy way also the g4-square!} 17. Qe4 $1 {Kramnik is a class act.
You can bank on him to find the most challenging and ambitious moves in the
position. After all, that's the reason why he played in such an aggressive
fashion in the opening.} (17. Nc3 Ne5 18. Qe4 Qg4+ 19. Qg2 Qxh4 $132 {gives
Black a lot of counterplay.}) 17... Qxc2 {Sjugirov goes for the most critical
continuation asking White what exactly is he trying to do.} (17... Re8 18. Bxb7
$5 (18. Qxg6 Ne5 19. Qe4 Ng6 $5 20. Qxg6 Qg4+ $11 {Sagar Shah: '='} 21. Kh1
Qh3+ 22. Kg1 Qg4+ $11) 18... Qc7 (18... Rxe4 19. Bxc8 $16) (18... Qxc2 19. Qc6
$1 Qxc6 (19... Qxb2 20. Bxa8 Qxa1 21. Qxd6 $18) 20. Bxc6 $16) 19. Qc6 Rac8 20.
Qxc7 Rxc7 21. Bd5 Rxc2 22. Na3 Bxa3 23. bxa3 Rc5 $11 {+/=. Black should be
able to hold the draw here.}) 18. Na3 {might have been interesting.} (18. Nc3 {
This is the most logical way to develop. The knight comes into the centre. In
such positions along with calculation, you need to develop a feel for the
dynamics, something which is possessed by Kramnik to a high degree.} Qxb2 (
18... Rae8 19. Qxg6 $1 $16) 19. Qxg6 Bc5 (19... Qxc3 20. Qxd6 Ne5 (20... Rad8 {
It is extremely difficult to assess positions like these. But say after} 21.
Rac1 Qe5 (21... Qxd3 22. Bxf7+ $18) (21... Qa5 22. Be4 (22. Bxb7 Qf5 $1 $13)
22... Nf6 23. Qc7 Qxc7 24. Rxc7 Nxe4 25. dxe4 $14) 22. Qxe5 Nxe5 23. Bxb7 Rxd3
$11 {/+=. White has a small edge thanks to his bishop being the superior minor
piece in an open position. But the number of pawns on both sides of the board
is equal and Black should be able to hold this one with accurate play.}) 21.
Rac1 Qd4 $5 {is the only move for Black.} (21... Qb2 22. Rfe1 Nxd3 23. Bxf7+ $1
Rxf7 24. Qxd3 $18) 22. Rc4 $1 (22. Bxf7+ $2 Rxf7 23. Qxd4 Nf3+ $19) 22... Qb2 (
22... Nxc4 23. Bxf7+ $18) 23. Re4 (23. Rxf4 Rad8 $19) 23... Nf3+ 24. Kg2 Nxh4+
25. Kh3 Nf3 26. g6 Ng5+ 27. Kh4 Nxe4 28. dxe4 $14 {[%csl Gh4] The king on h4
looks quite safe and in this position White stands better mainly because his
bishop is so strong on d5. A completely non-forcing and long variation to show
you how tricky and complicated the position is.}) (19... Be5 {is another
option to be considered. But White has a strong idea with} 20. Qh5 $1 {[%cal
Gg5g6]} Qxc3 21. g6 Nf6 (21... Rfd8 22. Rac1 Qd4 23. Bxf7+ $40) 22. gxf7+ Rxf7
23. Bxf7+ Kf8 24. Qh8+ Kxf7 25. Qxa8 $18) 20. Ne4 Qe5 {Now after Bb3 White has
a lot of threats in the position, but the question is instead of ...Qe5 what
should have Black played? His position looks already quite perilous.} (20...
Qd4 21. Bb3 Qxd3 22. Nf6+ $18) (20... Rad8 21. Rab1 Qd4 22. Bb3 Be7) (20... Ne5
21. Nf6+ Kh8 22. Qh7#) (20... Rae8 21. Rae1 $18 {[%csl Gd5,Ge1,Ge4,Gg6]}) 21.
Bb3 $1 $16 {1-0 (25) Kramnik,V (2760)-Sjugirov,S (2673) Doha 2014 CBM 164  
[Sagar Shah] The white rook is coming to e1 now. What should Black do?}) (18.
Qxg6 {[%cal Gg6d6]} Bc5 (18... Qxb2 19. Qxd6 Qxa1 20. Qxd7 $18) 19. Qh5 {
threatening g6.} Qxd3 20. g6 Qg3+ $1 21. Kh1 Qh3+ {would be a nice way to end
the game.}) 18... Bxa3 (18... Qxb2 19. Nc4 $18) 19. bxa3 Rad8 (19... Rae8 20.
Bxf7+ Kxf7 21. Qd5+ $16 Ke7 22. Rac1 Qa4 23. Rc4 Qa6 24. Rb1 $18 {with a
fierce attack.}) 20. Qxf4 Nc5 {and in spite of being a pawn down, it is clear
that Black is not much worse because White's position has so many weaknesses.})
12. g5 (12. Nc3 d4 13. Ne2 c5 14. c3 (14. f4 exf4 15. Bxf4 Qe7 $15) 14... Rc8
15. Kh1 Kh8 $13) 12... Nh5 13. exd5 cxd5 $44 {White can win the pawn in one of
two ways, but Black gets excellent counterplay on the dark squares, either way.
} 14. Nc3 (14. Bxd5+ Kh8 15. Nc3 Bc5 16. Kh2 (16. Bxb7 Rb8 17. Bg2 Ng3 18. Ne4
Nxf1 19. Bxf1 Be7 20. b3 Nc5 $15) 16... Be7 17. h4 Nc5 $44) 14... Nb6 (14... d4
15. Nb5) 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. Bxd5+ Kh8 17. Bxb7 Rb8 18. Bg2 Nf4 $132) 6... e5 7.
e4 ({White can also hesitate with the e2-e4 move and try to win the bishop
pair instead:} 7. h3 Bh5 8. g4 Bg6 9. Nh4 Bc5 (9... Nc5 $5 10. c4 Bd6) 10. e3
O-O 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. c4 d4 13. Nb3 dxe3 14. fxe3 Bd6 $13) {Here, I would
suggest} 7... Be7 $5 ({instead of the 'standard'} 7... dxe4 8. dxe4 Bc5 {
[#] My understanding is that Black takes on e4 out of necessity rather than by
his own will. The problem is that White can target the e5 and d5 pawns if
Black keeps the tension in the centre, so it seems necessary to release it
sooner or later. However, the arising structure, while obviously very solid
for Black, seems a bit easier for White to handle. In my experience, Black is
often on the backfoot here as White has an easier time developing a positional
initiative with moves like Nc4, a4(-a5), Qe1, Bd2-c3, Nh4-f5, etc. I provide
some illustrative examples for both sides below:} 9. Qe1 O-O 10. h3 Bh5 11. a4
(11. Nh4 Re8 12. Nc4 (12. Nf5 Bg6 13. g4 Nf8 (13... Bxf5 $142 14. exf5 e4 $1
$15) 14. Nb3 Bb6 15. Kh1 Ne6 16. Be3 Qc7 17. Rd1 Rad8 18. Qe2 Nf4 $15 {0-1 (46)
Christiansen,L (2595) -Beliavsky,A (2620) Brussels 1992}) 12... b5 (12... Qc7
13. Kh1 (13. b4 $142) 13... a5 14. Ne3 Nf8 15. Nef5 Ne6 $15 16. f4 exf4 17.
gxf4 Bg6 18. Ng3 Nd4 19. Qc3 b6 20. f5 $2 (20. e5 Nh5 $15) 20... Nh5 21. Nxh5
Bxh5 22. Bf4 Qe7 $19 {0-1 (41) Paragua,M (2526)-Harikrishna,P (2659) Beijing
2008}) 13. Na5 Qc7 14. a4 Bb6 15. Nb3 a6 16. Bg5 c5 (16... h6 17. Bd2 c5 $132
18. c4 {1-0 (56) Aronian,L (2562)-Bu,X (2553) Athens 2001} Nf8 $1 $13) 17. a5
Ba7 18. c4 Rab8 19. Nd2 h6 20. Be3 Nf8 $13 21. f4 exf4 22. Bxf4 {1-0 (59)
