20. Be3 Nf8 21. Nc5 Bxc5 22. Bxc5 Ne6 {1/2 (30) Markus,R (2625)-Beliavsky,A  
(2630) Ljubljana 2012} 23. Be3 $5 {[%cal Gf2f4]}) 8. h3 ({In the case of} 8.
Qe1 O-O 9. exd5 Nxd5 {we are ready to sacrifice the central pawn in the spirit
of the Marshall attack:} 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. Qxe5 Qd7 $44 {[%csl Rc1,Yc2,Rd2,Re5]
[%cal Gd5b4,Ge7f6] [#] Black has full compensation for the pawn and, it seems,
an easier play, as we can see from the variations below:} 12. Nb3 (12. Ne4 f5
13. Ng5 f4 $1) (12. a3 Rfe8 13. Qd4 Bf6 14. Qc4 Nb6 $44) 12... Rfe8 (12... a5
$5) 13. Qd4 Bf6 14. Qc4 b5 15. Qc5 Re2 $44) 8... Bh5 9. Qe1 ({White can also
approach the e-pawn with:} 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Re1 f6 11. d4 O-O 12. g4 Bf7 $13 {
when we get a complex position with mutual chances.} 13. Ne4 (13. dxe5 $6 Nf4
14. exf6 Nxf6 15. Bf1 Bc5 $36) 13... Re8 14. c4 Nc7 15. dxe5 Nxe5 16. Nxe5 fxe5
$11) 9... O-O $1 {The pawn sacrifice is the point, of course.} (9... dxe4 10.
dxe4 O-O 11. Nc4 Qc7 {-7...dxe4}) 10. Nh4 {Objectively speaking, it is
probably best for White not to accept the gift.} ({In the case of} 10. exd5
$140 Nxd5 11. g4 (11. Nxe5 Nb4 $1 $17) 11... Bg6 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. Qxe5 Bd6 $44
{[%csl Gd6,Gf4][%cal Gf7f5] Black gets loads of counterplay against White's
weakened kingside.}) 10... Re8 11. Nf5 Bf8 $11 {[%cal Gd7c5,Ga7a5] It is a
whole different story with the pawns on d3 and d5. Black has more space
compared to dxe4, dxe4 structures. White doesn't have access to the important
c4-square and d-file as in that position, so Black's position is quite
comfortable here, as we can see from practical examples below:} 12. Nb3 (12.
Nf3 Nc5 (12... a5 13. a4 Nc5 14. Nh2 Ne6 $132 15. Bd2 Bg6 16. Nf3 Bxf5 17. exf5
Nc5 18. Nh4 Qb6 $17 {[%cal Ge5e4] 0-1 Varadero (2574)-dkuljasevic (2716)/
chess24.com 2017 (68)}) (12... dxe4 13. dxe4 Nc5 14. N3h4 Qb6 15. b3 Qa6 16. f3
Ne6 17. Ne3 Rad8 18. Bb2 $10 {Gufeld-Lputian, Hastings 1986}) 13. N3h4 a5 14.
Rb1 Ne6 15. g4 Bg6 16. Bd2 Nf4 $15 {Botterill - Hodgson, Bath zt 1987}) 12...
a5 13. a4 Nc5 14. Nxc5 Bxc5 15. Be3 Bb4 (15... Bxe3 $11) 16. c3 Bf8 17. f3 Bg6
18. Nh4 Nh5 19. Qf2 Qd7 20. Kh2 Bd6 21. Rae1 Bc7 22. Bb6 {1/2-1/2 Pantsulaia,L
(2613)-Vitiugov,N (2721) /Gjakova 2016} *

