{[%evp 0,40,24,20,20,-6,10,-5,2,-19,0,14,10,-10,15,4,24,18,21,18,29,13,12,-6,
19,14,16,-13,-5,-15,-13,1,10,-3,-2,29,37,20,21,13,11,-35,-4]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3
Bg4 3. Bg2 e6 4. c4 c6 5. O-O Nf6 {Double fianchetto is probably the least
critical approach against the Bg4 system. Black has an easy development scheme
and faces no pressure in the centre. Double fianchetto is more unpleasant for
Black if he develops the bishop to f5 because the e2-e4 move comes with a
tempo and usually sends the bishop to a passive h7-square.} 6. d3 {This is the
most clever move order if White wants to develop the bishop to b2.} ({In the
case of} 6. b3 {White immediately shows his cards and Black can achieve his
ideal piece setup easily:} Nbd7 7. Bb2 Bd6 8. d3 O-O 9. Nbd2 a5 10. a3 {
[#] Black's idea now is to gain space in the centre with ...e6-e5. Kasparov's}
Bh5 $5 {is one of the good options, serving as prophylaxis against h3, Nh4, g4
plan.} (10... Re8 $5) 11. Qc2 (11. Re1 {in the style of Richard Reti, is too
passive and Black gets nice play after} e5 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Nf1 Re8 14. Ne3 d4
$15) 11... Re8 12. e4 (12. h3 h6 $1 {preserves the bishop from exchange for
the knight.} 13. e4 dxe4 14. dxe4 Bg6 $11) 12... dxe4 13. dxe4 e5 $11 {Black
establishes symmetrical structure in the centre, with an important detail that
d4-square can potentially be vulnerable for White.} 14. Nh4 Bc5 (14... b5 $5
$132 15. Nf5 Bf8 16. cxb5 cxb5 $36 {[%cal Gd7c5]}) 15. Ndf3 Qb6 16. Rad1 Bf8
17. Rb1 Nc5 18. Bxe5 Ncxe4 19. Bd4 Bc5 20. Bxc5 Qxc5 21. b4 axb4 22. axb4 $11 {
1/2-1/2 (28) Leko,P (2745) -Kasparov,G (2849) Wijk aan Zee 2001}) 6... Be7 {
is our preferred setup in this repertoire. White can take advantage of it by
playing} 7. b3 {now, with the idea that e7 is a more passive square for the
bishop than d6. After} Nbd7 8. Bb2 O-O 9. Nbd2 a5 10. a3 Re8 11. Qc2 {[#]
Black's best plan is to play} Bd6 {anyway, which is basically the same
position that we already examined, only with the bishop on g4 instead of h5.
It's not a big deal, though - Black is still completely fine, as evidenced by
the game below:} 12. h3 Bh5 13. Bc3 (13. e4 dxe4 14. dxe4 e5 15. Nh4 b5 $5 $132
) 13... Qe7 14. e4 dxe4 15. dxe4 e5 $11 16. Bb2 Bc5 17. Nh4 Nf8 18. Ndf3 {
0-1 (52) Abeln,M (2353)-Movsesian,S (2628) Enschede 2005} Bxf3 19. Nxf3 Ng6 20.
h4 Rad8 $132 *

