1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. b3 Bd6 {This is my primary
recommendation. Black wants to play e6-e5 as soon as possible. The idea is to
keep the knight on b8, so Black can answer cxd5 with cxd5 followed by Nc6.} 6.
Bb2 O-O 7. Qc2 $6 e5 $1 8. Be2 $5 {Duda tried this move twice, but not with a
big success} (8. cxd5 {is mainline and is analyzed in the next games.}) 8... e4
$1 {Black shouldn't waste time} 9. Ng5 (9. Nd4 {was probably better, but Black
is still OK after} a6 10. g4 $1 Re8 11. g5 c5 $1 $17) 9... h6 10. h4 {Typical
way to play for White} Re8 $1 ({Black should not accept the sacrifice} 10...
hxg5 11. hxg5 Ng4 (11... Nh7 12. f4) 12. cxd5 Qxg5 (12... cxd5 13. Nxe4 $1 $18)
13. Nxe4 $18) 11. Nh3 (11. O-O-O {was possible, but Duda doesn't want to
calculate hxg5 all the time} Na6 {[%cal Rd8e7]}) 11... Na6 (11... dxc4 {
it was probably better to start with this move} 12. bxc4 Na6) 12. a3 (12. cxd5
$5) 12... dxc4 $1 13. Bxc4 (13. bxc4 {If White takes with a pawn, then the
c5-knight will be very strong because it can't be attacked with a pawn.} Nc5 {
[%cal Rc5d3]}) 13... b5 $1 {Black immediately seize the initiative} 14. Be2 b4
$1 {Now Black activates his a6-knight.} 15. Nd1 bxa3 16. Bxa3 Nb4 (16... Bxa3 {
was simpler} 17. Rxa3 Nb4 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Rc8g4]}) 17. Bxb4 Bxb4 18. g3 Ng4
19. Ra2 Qf6 $17 20. Kf1 Bf5 21. Kg2 (21. Nb2 $1 {[%cal Rb2c4]}) 21... Rad8 22.
Nc3 a5 $1 23. Nf4 Qe5 (23... g5 24. hxg5 hxg5) 24. Rc1 Rd6 25. Qd1 Nf6 26. h5
Red8 27. Nb1 g5 $1 28. hxg6 fxg6 29. Qh1 Kg7 30. Na3 Bxa3 31. Rxa3 g5 32. Nh5+
