1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 c6 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 Nbd7 {This is the favourite move of GM
Shirov. The main idea is to prepare quick 5...e5.} 5. Qc2 e6 {This is not very
ambitious, and in my opinion, White can hope for an advantage here, but Dreev
doesn't want to enter a sharp theoretical battle but develop his pieces.} (5...
e5 {is more ambitious and it is analyzed in the game - Topalov - Anand}) 6. b3
b6 7. Bb2 Bb7 8. Rg1 $5 {Typical move for this setup. White is preparing g4
and is ready to evacuate the king on the queenside. The drawback of this move
is that White can't castle short anymore.} (8. Be2 {is the calmer continuation.
} Rc8 9. O-O Bd6 10. Rad1 O-O 11. e4 c5 (11... dxc4 $1 12. bxc4 c5) 12. exd5
exd5 13. d4 $14 {0-1 (29) Bauer,C (2595)-Dreev,A (2689) Playchess. com INT 2004
}) 8... c5 $1 {correct decision. Black needs to opt for quick counterplay. As
the old rule says: A flang attack should be met by a strike in the centre} (
8... Be7 9. g4 O-O 10. g5 $16 {[%cal Rh2h4,Rf1d3,Re1c1] White has a dangerous
attack}) 9. Be2 dxc4 {Dreev's decision is typical for this structure, but it
was probably too early to release the tension} ({The engine suggests} 9... h5
$5 10. cxd5 exd5 11. O-O-O {[%cal Ra7a6,Rb6b5,Ra8c8] With a very sharp
position where is not that clear which attack is faster.}) 10. bxc4 Ng4 $5 {
I believe this is an inaccuracy, usually Black is playing this only after
White's pawn is already on "h4"} ({fascinating defensive idea is} 10... h6 11.
g4 g5 {[%cal Ra7a6,Rd8c7,Rf8g7]}) 11. Ne4 (11. h3 $1 {was simple and strong}
Nge5 12. O-O-O) 11... Qc7 12. Nfg5 Ngf6 13. f4 Be7 14. Nc3 a6 15. O-O-O $6 b5
$3 {powerful pawn sacrifice. Dreev didn't hesitate to take the initiative} 16.
cxb5 (16. g4 {was the better way to continue}) 16... c4 $1 17. bxa6 $2 {
One mistake never comes alone. Black is already winning. There are too many
open files in front of White's king} Bxa6 $19 {The rest was just technique.
Black easily converts his advantage and mates White's weak king.} 18. g4 Nc5
19. Nf3 O-O 20. Ne5 Nd3+ 21. Nxd3 cxd3 22. Bxd3 Bxd3 23. Qxd3 Nd5 24. Kb1 Qa5
25. e4 Nb4 26. Qb5 $1 Qa7 27. a4 Rfb8 28. Qe2 Nc6 29. Rg3 Rb4 30. Rc1 Rab8 31.
Nb5 Qxa4 32. Rxc6 Rxb2+ $1 33. Kxb2 Rxb5+ 34. Kc1 Ba3+ 35. Rxa3 Qxa3+ 0-1

