{[%evp 0,36,38,21,30,-10,25,25,36,42,45,25,45,-12,21,27,22,8,2,2,0,-5,-10,-12,
-3,-12,-9,-9,-15,-24,-7,-3,-8,-8,-11,-11,-1,-18,-22] I am providing you with
the analysis of IM Renato Quintillano. I believe he covered very well the
Meran with b3.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Nf3 Nbd7 {Now let's
check some sidelines for White on the 6th move. The knight is already on f3
this time, so White's options mainly intend to avoid the sharp Meran positions.
} 6. b3 {This is the most popular one after the main moves, but I don't think
it promises much for White. It does avoid Meran ideas but on the other hand
Black gets a favourable version of positions seen in Chapter 4. A lot of
different moves have been tried as well. Some of them are simply harmless, but
it is always good to be aware of unusual ideas, especially when everyone is
testing everything.} (6. cxd5 {is the second most played, but it's just
another move that only makes Black's task in the opening easier.} exd5 7. Bd3
Bd6 {We have a sort of Exchange Variation without the pin on f6, which
considerably increases Black's freedom to develop.} 8. O-O ({The
pseudo-aggressive plan} 8. Qc2 O-O 9. Bd2 Re8 10. O-O-O $2 {doesn't seem good.
White's attack is too slow, while Black's offensive on the queenside looks
more dangerous. Black even has more than one good option here, but I like the
following game by Shirov:} c5 $1 11. dxc5 Nxc5 12. Nd4 a6 13. f3 b5 14. Kb1 b4
15. Nce2 Nxd3 16. Qxd3 a5 $19 {[%cal Gc8a6] ;Agdestein,S (2590)-Shirov,A (2655)
/Gausdal m 1992 (1)/0-1, and White is in trouble.}) 8... O-O 9. Qc2 {White can
keep making some good developing moves, but in the end, the only idea worthy
of considering is the advance e3-e4, which nonetheless doesn't offer chances
of an advantage.} ({Passive play by White allows Black to keep making
significant strategic improvements of his position, for example:} 9. b3 Re8 10.
Qc2 Nf8 11. Bb2 Bg4 $1 12. Nd2 Bh5 13. Rfe1 Bg6 $15 {Vyzmanavin,A (2605)
-Khalifman, A (2645)/Groningen PCA 1993 (2)/1/2-1/2, and Black's position
already seems more pleasant to me.}) ({In one of my games White tried} 9. Rb1 {
, but the Minority Attack seems much less annoying here, as Black has no
problems developing his counterplay on the kingside.} Re8 10. Qc2 Qe7 11. a3
Ne4 $17 {[%cal Gd7f6] ;Gauche,C (2250)-Quintiliano Pinto,R (2430)/
Florianopolis 3rd 2016 (2)/0-1, and I had the initiative.}) 9... Re8 10. Re1
Nf8 11. h3 $1 {This at least avoids the manoeuvre Bg4-h5-g6 which forces an
advantageous exchange for Black.} Bd7 12. Bd2 Rc8 13. Rad1 {Sidorov,A (2438)
-Lastin, A (2583)/RUS-ch Higher League 60th 2007 (1)/1/2-1/2 Now after
something sensible like} h6 {, White's useful moves have come to an end, and
the only plan is to open the centre. Nevertheless, after} 14. e4 dxe4 15. Nxe4
Nxe4 16. Bxe4 Be6 $11 {, Black has a comfortable position against the isolated
pawn.}) (6. a3 {is the most flexible and also a multi-purposing move. White
anticipates b5-b4 (which can be considered after the typical dxc4 followed by
b7-b5), the a2-square might be useful to retreat the bishop, and most
important is that White doesn't define the setup yet. Still, this is very
subtle stuff and in practice, Black gets a free tempo compared to other
theoretical positions.} Bd6 7. Bd3 ({The attempt to find a better use for
White's last move with} 7. b4 {doesn't offer any advantage, as can be seen in
the following game by Gelfand:} O-O 8. Bb2 Qe7 9. Qc2 a6 10. Bd3 dxc4 11. Bxc4
e5 {Bauer,C (2641)-Gelfand,B (2724)/Biel GM 2005 (2)/0-1, and Black is ok. In
some positions, it is possible to exploit White's structure on the queenside
in Black's favour with a6-a5.}) 7... O-O 8. O-O e5 $5 {Even in the main lines
of theory, this advance isn't considered objectively bad for Black, which
means that in sidelines, it is probably good, too.} (8... dxc4 {is also
possible, of course, transposing to more critical lines of the Meran.} 9. Bxc4
b5 10. Bd3 {Mamedyarov,S (2782)-Shankland,S (2709)/Saint Louis Blitz blitz
