1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Bf5 {This way of developing the bishop
leads to the so-called Lasker system. For two main reasons, the last move is a
bit mysterious. Firstly, after the probable d2-d3, the bishop will hit onto a
stonewall, with apparently few chances of exerting effective activity.
Secondly, the bishop is constantly exposed to Nh4. The second question is
easier to answer. At this stage, the threat Nh4 is not real (we will soon find
out why). Later, Black will prepare the bishop's retreat to h7 by playing ...
h7-h6. The first issue is more complex. Black will need to coordinate his army
in such a way that the bishop will be useful, one way or another. I will
indicate a few such cases later in some concrete lines. I usually get this
position with white and in practice, I have tried several setups. I will offer
viable solutions against all of them.} 5. cxd5 {For many decades, this has
been considered an effective way of retaining a small but stable plus.
Abstractly, this exchange is a bit premature, since it helps Black clear the
c6-square for his queen's knight.} ({It is useful to mention that} 5. Nh4 {
is premature due to} Be4 6. f3 Bxb1 7. Rxb1 {, leaving the knight misplaced on
h4. This applies to many later moments and I will not mention it too often.})
5... cxd5 6. Qb3 {The logical complement of the previous move.} (6. O-O {
does not make much sense, since it allows Black to complete his development
harmoniously.} Nc6 7. d4 (7. d3 e5 8. Bg5 Be7 9. Nc3 Be6 10. e4 O-O $5 11. Bxf6
Bxf6 12. Ng5 Bxg5 13. exd5 Bxd5 14. Bxd5 Nd4) 7... e6 8. Nc3 Bd6 9. Nh4 (9. Qb3
a6 $11 {[%cal Gc6a5]} 10. Qxb7 $2 Na5) 9... Bg4 10. h3 Bh5 11. Bg5 h6 12. Bxf6
Qxf6 $11 {Lujambio,A (2011)-Garcia Moretti,G (2205) ICCF email 2016 (1-0, 26)})
6... Nc6 $1 {Black can defend the pawn on b7 in many ways, but all of them
have at least minor drawbacks. Fortunately, he can ignore the threat and
continue developing.} ({The most popular move is} 6... Qb6 {ensuring White
pleasant play after} 7. Qxb6 axb6 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. d3 $14) 7. Qxb7 {Other moves
do not justify the early queen's development.} (7. O-O e5 $5 {Black continues
to play in Gambit style.} ({After defending e5, Black can safely play} 7... Qd7
$11 {, though.}) 8. Qxb7 Bd7 9. Bh3 Bxh3 10. Qxc6+ Bd7 11. Qa6 {Bruce,R (1941)
-Anderson,G (2333) ICCF email 2019 (0-1, 31)} e4 12. Nd4 Bc5 13. Nb3 Bb6 14. d4
O-O $15) (7. d4 {leaves the light diagonal clear for the bishop and the
e4-square available to the knight. For these reasons,} Qb6 {is entirely
playable now.} (7... Qd7 {is also good.} 8. Nc3 e6 9. Ne5 Qc7 10. Bf4 Qb6 11.
Qxb6 axb6 12. Nb5 Bb4+ 13. Bd2 Bxd2+ 14. Kxd2 Ke7 15. Rhc1 Rhc8 16. f3 h6 17.
e3 Ne8 18. Bf1 f6 19. Nd3 e5 $11 {Andersen,L (2201)-Rasmussen,E (2328) ICCF
email 2007 (½-½, 34)}) 8. Qxb6 axb6 9. O-O (9. Nc3 e6 10. O-O Bb4 11. Bd2 Ne4
$15) 9... Bxb1 10. Rxb1 Rxa2 11. Bf4 e6 12. Rfc1 Ra8 13. Ra1 Rxa1 14. Rxa1 Kd7
15. Ne5+ Nxe5 16. dxe5 Ne4 17. Bxe4 dxe4 18. Rd1+ Kc8 19. Rd4 Bc5 20. Rxe4 Rd8
$11 {Owens,J (2222)-Sisak,R (2138) ICCF email 2017 (½-½, 26)}) 7... Bd7 {
Another paradoxical move. Right after sacrificing the pawn, Black retreats
with his bishop. The main threat is ...Rb8 followed by ...Nb4. In the next
phase, White will have to lose a couple of tempi in order to retreat with his
queen to d1. This way, Black's loss of time is irrelevant.} 8. Qb3 (8. Bh3 {
invests a tempo on placing the bishop on an exposed square, without reaching
anything concrete.} e6 9. Qb3 Rb8 10. Qd1 {At this height, Black has several
good plans.} Bd6 (10... e5 $5 11. Bxd7+ Qxd7 12. d4 Bb4+ 13. Bd2 Bxd2+ 14. Qxd2
Ne4 15. Qe3 Qb7 16. Qb3 Qxb3 17. axb3 exd4 18. O-O Kd7 $11) (10... h5 11. d4 h4
$15) 11. d4 O-O 12. Nc3 Qb6 $44 {All Black's pieces are ready to contribute to
developing the pressure and initiative, while White is underdeveloped and his
bishop on h3 passive.} 13. O-O Rfc8 14. Na4 Qb5 15. b3 Nb4 16. Bd2 Ne4 17. Bxb4
Bxb4 18. Ne5 Be8 $17 {Peng,L (2431)-Sadubayev,A (2190) Tornelo INT 2020 (½-½,
36)}) (8. Na3 $2 {defends c2 but looks awkward.} Rb8 9. Qa6 e5 10. d3 Bc5 11.
Qa4 e4 $19 {Royakkers,G-Duijker,R (2288) Amsterdam 2004 (½-½, 20)}) 8... e5 {
The most restrictive move order.} (8... Rb8 $6 {allows White to devfiate from
the main line with} 9. Qc3 {controlling e5.} e6 (9... Ne4 10. Qc2 e5 11. d3 $14
) 10. O-O Bd6 11. b3 $14) 9. O-O {White has problems fighting against the
threat ...e5-e4.} (9. d4 {runs into} Bb4+ 10. Bd2 (10. Kf1 exd4 $17 {Bruce,R  
(1774)-Schuller,J (2381) ICCF email 2013 (0-1, 34)} 11. Nxd4 $2 Nxd4 12. Qxb4
Nc2) 10... Rb8 11. Qd1 Bxd2+ 12. Nbxd2 (12. Qxd2 Ne4 {[%cal Gd8a5] followed by
...Qa5 puts White in a difficult situation.}) 12... e4 13. Ne5 e3 14. fxe3 Nxe5
15. dxe5 Ng4 16. Nf1 O-O $15) (9. d3 {has the same drawback: it allows an
early check on b4, against which White does not have an optimal defence.} Rb8
10. Qd1 Bb4+ 11. Nfd2 {Relatively best.} (11. Nbd2 e4 12. dxe4 dxe4 13. Ng5 e3
14. fxe3 Ng4 $19) (11. Nc3 d4 12. a3 Ba5 13. b4 dxc3 14. bxa5 Qxa5 $19) (11.
Bd2 e4 12. dxe4 dxe4 13. Ng5 e3 $17 14. fxe3 Ng4 {with strong initiative.}) (
11. Kf1 $146 O-O $5) 11... h5 {Simple and ambitious.} (11... Qc8 {is also
playable.} 12. Nc3 Bh3 13. O-O h5 14. Nxd5 h4 {Khismatullin,D (2609)-Saric,I  
(2650) Gjakova 2016 (0-1, 24)} 15. Nxf6+ $1 gxf6 16. Nf3 Nd4 17. Nxd4 Bxg2 18.
Kxg2 hxg3 19. hxg3 Qh3+ 20. Kf3 exd4 21. Qa4+ Kf8 22. Bf4 Qh5+ 23. Kg2 Qh3+ {
drawn}) ({The first game featuring 6...Nc6 continued with the illogical} 11...
Qa5 $2 {Topp,M (2130)-Reinhold,K (2152) Germany 2003 (½-½, 44)}) 12. a3 Bc5
13. h3 (13. b4 $2 {loses to} Bxf2+ $1 14. Kxf2 Ng4+ {with a decisive attack.})
(13. e3 h4 14. Nc3 {Wenner,T (2147)-Thorfinnsson,B (2385) Rhodes 2013 (0-1, 53)
} Bf5 15. b4 Bb6 16. Nb3 Qd7 $5 {with excellent compensation for the pawn.})
13... O-O (13... Be6 14. Nc3 O-O 15. O-O Qd7 16. Kh2 Be7 17. Nf3 d4 18. Nb1 Bb3
19. Qe1 Bd5 $44 {Au Cardero,R (2289)-Jacobs,R (2387) ICCF email 2018 (½-½,
41)}) 14. O-O Qc8 15. Kh2 h4 $44 16. g4 Ne7 17. Nc3 Be6 18. e3 Ng6 19. g5 Nh7
$44) 9... Rb8 10. Qd1 e4 11. Ne1 h5 {After making considerable progress in the
centre, Black starts a simple kingside attack. Being underdeveloped, White
cannot enjoy his extra pawn.} 12. d3 (12. h4 {as played in Calza,G-Ragnarsson,
J (2045) ICCF email 2014 (½-½, 28) wastes time and weakens the kingside.} d4
$5 $146 13. Na3 (13. d3 e3 14. fxe3 Bd6 $17) 13... g5 14. hxg5 Ng4 15. d3 e3
$17) 12... h4 13. Bf4 {Relatively safest. White prepares to consolidate his
kingside with Bxg3.} ({After} 13. Nc3 hxg3 14. hxg3 {the most active
continuation is} e3 $5 15. Bxe3 {Taking the bull by the horns.} (15. Nxd5 Nxd5
16. Bxd5 Qg5 17. Bg2 {Paul,J (2263)-Pitl,G (2394) Germany 2015 (0-1, 31)} Qh5
18. Nf3 Ne5 19. fxe3 Ng4 20. Qe1 Bd6 21. Rb1 Rc8 22. Bd2 Rc2 23. Bb4 Bc7 $17) (
15. fxe3 Bd6 $19) 15... d4 16. Bf4 dxc3 17. Bxb8 cxb2 18. Rb1 Qxb8 19. Qc2 Qb5
20. Qxb2 $1 $146 (20. Rxb2 $2 Qh5 21. Nf3 Nd4 {0-1 Vitouch,A (2325)-Mons,L  
(2435) Austria 2015}) 20... Qh5 21. Nf3 Bd6 22. Rfc1 O-O 23. Qb7 Ne5 24. Qxa7
Nfg4 $13 {All Black's minor pieces are ready to sustain the queen during the
consistent kingside attack. White's material advantage should reach for
maintaining the equality only.}) (13. dxe4 $2 {is bad because of} hxg3 $1 (
13... dxe4 14. Bf4 hxg3 15. Bxg3 {transposes to the main line}) 14. hxg3 dxe4
15. Nc3 Qa5 16. Bf4 Rxb2 17. Nxe4 (17. Rc1 Bb4 18. Nxe4 Nxe4 19. Bxe4 Rd2 20.
Qb3 Nd4 $19) 17... Nxe4 18. Bxe4 Qh5 19. g4 Qxg4+ 20. Ng2 g5 21. Rc1 gxf4 22.
Bxc6 Bxc6 23. Rxc6 Qh3 24. f3 Be7 {0-1 Petrov,N (2456)-Van Foreest,J (2547)
Groningen 2015}) 13... hxg3 (13... Rxb2 $13 {is also playable.}) 14. Bxg3 {
Now and on the next move, the bishop is too precious to exchange it for the
rook.} (14. Bxb8 $2 gxf2+ 15. Rxf2 Qxb8 $19) 14... Nh5 15. dxe4 (15. Nc3 Nxg3
16. hxg3 Qf6 {transposes}) (15. Bxb8 $2 Qxb8 16. e3 Nf6 17. f4 Ng4 $19) 15...
Nxg3 16. hxg3 Qf6 {Heading for h6.} (16... Qg5 {is equally good.}) 17. Nc3 Qh6
18. Nf3 Ne5 19. Re1 Bc5 20. e3 (20. Nxe5 Qh2+ 21. Kf1 Bh3 $19) 20... Bg4 21.
Qa4+ Bd7 22. Qd1 {White does not have anything else than accepting a draw by
repetition.} (22. Qc2 $2 Nxf3+ 23. Bxf3 d4 24. exd4 Qh2+ 25. Kf1 Bxd4 26. Bg2
O-O 27. Rad1 Rb4 {[%cal Gd7c8,Gc8a6] Threatening either ...Bc8-a6+ or ...Bxb4
followed by ...Bb5+.} 28. a3 Rc4 $17 {[%cal Gd7b5] Threatening ...Bb5.}) 22...
Bg4 23. Qa4+ {½-½ Artemiev,V (2697)-Petrosian,T (2589) Moscow 2018} (23. Rb1
$2 Nxf3+ 24. Bxf3 Qh5 $5 25. Kg2 (25. Bxg4 $2 Qh1#) 25... Qh3+ 26. Kg1 Bb4 {
White cannot parry the combined threats along the h- and b-files.} 27. exd5 (
27. Rc1 Bxc3 28. Rxc3 Bxf3 29. Qxf3 Qh2+ 30. Kf1 Qh1+ 31. Qxh1 Rxh1+ 32. Ke2
Rxb2+ $19) 27... Bxf3 28. Qxf3 Bxc3 29. bxc3 Rxb1 30. Rxb1 Qh2+ 31. Kf1 Qh1+
32. Qxh1 Rxh1+ 33. Ke2 Rxb1 $19) (23. Kf1 $2 Rxb2 $19) *

