1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Bf5 5. Qb3 {This is a more refined attempt
at causing some queenside discomfort. The last move is known since 1940. Even
more remarkable, this move order was used by Fischer in 1970 in the game
quoted below. It means that the American had anticipated 6...Nc6, examined in
Line 1. Since ...Nb8-c6 is not available, Black has to defend his pawn after
all. However, a transposition to the pleasant lines for White is impossible.}
Qb6 6. d3 {The most consistent move. White plans Be3, inducing the exchange on
b3. Before moving on, we have to check what happens after exchanges on b6 and
d5, in either move order.} (6. cxd5 Qxb3 $1 (6... cxd5 7. Qxb6 axb6 8. Nc3 Nc6
9. d3 $14) 7. axb3 cxd5 {It is White who has the isolated double pawns now and
not Black. This prevents him from gaining an advantage.} 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. d3 (9.
Nh4 {is premature.} Be4 10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. d3 e6 12. O-O exd3 13. Bxc6+ bxc6 14.
exd3 Nd5 $11) 9... e5 $1 {Taking the available space.} ({Fischer's game
continued with} 9... e6 10. O-O Be7 11. Be3 Ng4 12. Bf4 O-O 13. e4 dxe4 14.
dxe4 Bg6 15. e5 $14 {with certain initiative, Fischer, R-Polugaevsky, L Palma
de Mallorca 1970 (½-½, 38) I should mention that this was the first time
when Fischer started with 1.c4. Previously, he had played it in a simul game.
Developing the comment above, I can only admire him for understanding the
small nuances in an opening he had not played before.}) 10. Bg5 {The critical
move, putting pressure on Black's centre.} (10. O-O a6 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. e4
Bxe4 13. dxe4 Ndb4 $11) 10... Be6 11. O-O a6 {Preventing Nb5 and preparing to
castle long.} (11... h6 $5 $146 12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. Nh4 O-O-O 14. f4 exf4 15.
Rxf4 Kb8 16. Rxf6 Nd4 {[%cal Gf8e7] Black has lost a pawn and his structure
has been weakened. However, White's queenside pawns are also weak and ...Be7
is an issue. Black seems to have normal compensation for the pawn.}) 12. Nh4 (
12. d4 e4 $15 {Gagare,S (2407)-Burmakin,V (2575) Montcada 2013 (½-½, 98)})
12... O-O-O 13. f4 exf4 14. Rxf4 Bc5+ 15. Kh1 Nh5 {The simplest way of
achieving counterplay.} (15... Be3 16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. Rxf6 h5 $44) 16. Bxd8 Nxf4
17. gxf4 Rxd8 18. f5 Bd7 19. Bxd5 (19. Nxd5 $6 Bf2 20. Nf3 Bxf5 $15) 19... Be8
20. Nf3 Nb4 21. Be4 f6 $44 {[%cal Ge8f7] Black is very active and his
dark-squared bishop is threatening. The immediate threat is ...Bf7, dooming
the pawn on b3.} 22. Rd1 Be3 23. d4 Bf7 24. d5 Kc7 25. Kg2 g6 26. fxg6 hxg6 27.
h4 Kd6 $11) (6. Qxb6 axb6 7. cxd5 {should be answered with} Nxd5 $1 {deviating
from White's dream line. There are certain problems on White's queenside. At
the same time, Black's doubled pawns are not weak, since they form a compact
group together with the pawn on c6.} 8. Nc3 (8. O-O Bxb1 9. Rxb1 Rxa2 $15) (8.
d3 Nb4 9. Na3 Rxa3 10. bxa3 Nc2+ 11. Kd2 Nxa1 12. Bb2 f6 13. Rxa1 e5 $15) 8...
Nxc3 9. dxc3 Nd7 10. O-O (10. Nd4 $6 Bg6 11. h4 h5 12. f4 e5 $1) (10. c4 g6 11.
Nd4 Bg7 12. Nxf5 gxf5 $17 {White faces problems with his queenside development.
}) 10... e5 (10... b5 11. Nd4 Bg6 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Bxc6 {[%csl Gb5,Gd7][%cal
Gf1d1]} O-O-O 14. a4 $36) 11. a4 Bd6 $11) 6... e6 7. Be3 $1 {White maintains
the tension still.} ({One more indication regarding the move order. In the
event of} 7. cxd5 Qxb3 8. axb3 {Black should play} exd5 {, which was not
available in a similar line above.} (8... cxd5 9. Nc3 {transposes to Fischer's
game, since Black has defined his central structure.}) 9. Bd2 {Black is solid
and White has a small structural defect. White's main plan is to put his
b-pawn into motion.} Na6 10. Na3 Be7 11. Nc2 O-O 12. Nfd4 Bd7 13. b4 Nc7 14.
Nb3 Nfe8 (14... Rfd8 $6 {was played in Eljanov,P (2739)-Beliavsky,A (2602)
Baku 2016  (1-0, 78) This move does not contribute too much to global harmony
and well-being.} 15. Be3 Nb5 16. Bc5 $14) 15. Be3 Nb5 16. Bc5 Ned6 $1 17. Ncd4
Rfe8 18. Kd2 {Black is very solid and it is hard to indicate a concrete plan
for White. Black should just improve his position slowly.} h5 $5 19. h3 g6 $5
$11) (7. Nh4 Bg6 {may transpose to the lines below.}) (7. O-O Nbd7 8. Be3 {
runs into} Bc5 $1 9. Bxc5 Nxc5 10. Qc3 a5 11. Rc1 Ncd7 12. cxd5 exd5 $11) 7...
Qxb3 8. axb3 a6 {White has opened the a-file for his rook and has some hopes
for launching the queenside attack with b3-b4-b5. The latter will require some
time investment, though. I must confess that I have never tried this system in
practice. I have played it in similar positions with 4...Bg4, though. AT this
stage of theory, I believe that it is White's most consistent try to maintain
the tension and outplay his opponent in the queenless middlegame.} 9. Nh4 {
The best try.} (9. Bd4 Nbd7 10. Bc3 {Nepomniachtchi,I (2784)-Carlsen,M  (2863)
chess24.com INT 2020 (½-½, 54)} h6 $1 $146 {solves Black's problems with his
bishop.} 11. Nbd2 (11. b4 dxc4 12. dxc4 Ne4 $11) 11... Bd6 12. O-O O-O 13. Rfe1
e5 {Due to the threat ..e5-e4, the bishop is well placed on f5 now.} 14. e4
dxe4 15. dxe4 Be6 {Chances are about equal in this almost symmetrical position.
} 16. b4 (16. Bf1 b5 17. b4 a5 18. bxa5 b4 19. Bd4 Bc7 20. Be3 Bxa5 21. Nb3 Bc7
$11) 16... c5 {The most resolute way of neutralising White's light pressure.}
17. bxc5 Nxc5 18. Bxe5 (18. Bf1 Ncd7 19. b4 b6 {[%cal Gd6c7,Ga6a5] followed by
...Bc7 and ...a6-a5.}) 18... Bxe5 19. Nxe5 Rfd8 20. Nf1 a5 21. f3 Nfd7 22. Nxd7
Rxd7 {Black has full compensation for the pawn.} 23. b4 (23. Ne3 Rd2 $132)
23... Nb3 24. Ra3 Bxc4 25. Ne3 b5 $11) 9... Bg6 10. Bd4 (10. h3 $5 {aims at
preventing ...Bh5 followed by ...h7-h6 and ...g7-g5.} Nbd7 11. O-O $146 a5 12.
Nc3 Bb4 13. Rfc1 O-O 14. Rc2 Rfd8 15. Nxg6 (15. Na2 Be7) 15... hxg6 16. d4 Ne8
$11) 10... Nbd7 11. Bc3 {Preparing b3-b4.} (11. Nxg6 hxg6 {frees Black from
the slight worries regarding the kingside tension.} 12. h4 (12. Bc3 g5 13. Nd2
g4 14. h3 gxh3 15. Bxh3 Bd6 16. e3 Ke7 17. Ke2 b5 $11) 12... e5 13. Bc3 d4 14.
Bd2 (14. Ba5 Be7 15. Nd2 O-O 16. Nf3 b6 17. Bd2 a5 $11 {stabilising the
queenside.}) {Thybo,J (2568)-Ozen,D (2397) Tornelo INT 2021 (1-0, 57)} 14...
Nc5 15. Ra3 Kd7 16. b4 Ne6 17. Ra2 Bd6 18. O-O Ng4 19. Na3 f5 $13 {None of the
players has concrete threats yet and the position remains unclear.}) (11. h3 e5
12. Bc3 d4 13. Ba5 (13. Bd2 Nc5) 13... Be7 14. Kd1 O-O 15. Nxg6 (15. Kc2 e4 $1
{Now is another moment when the bishop is useful.} 16. Nxg6 exd3+ 17. exd3 fxg6
$1 $132 {Black's better development and the pressure along the f-file offer
him normal play.}) 15... hxg6 16. Kc2 Rfe8 $13 {[%cal Gg6g5,Gd7f8,Gf8e6] Black
has several ways of proceeding, for instance ...Nf8-e6 or/and ...g6-g5. In all
these lines after ...d5-d4, the bishop on g2 faces the same problems as the
bishop on f5. It hits onto a rock (c6) and is not easy to convert into a
strong attacking piece.}) 11... Bh5 $1 {A good moment to avoid the exchange.}
12. Nd2 h6 13. h3 (13. b4 d4 14. Bxd4 Bxb4 $11 {[%cal Ga6a5]}) 13... g5 14.
Nhf3 Bg6 15. O-O Bg7 16. b4 O-O 17. Nb3 Rac8 18. Na5 Rc7 19. Rfc1 (19. cxd5
Nxd5 20. d4 Re8 $11 {[%cal Ge6e5]}) 19... Rfc8 $11 {[%cal Gf6e8] Possibly
followed by ...Ne8-d6. In the event of exchanging the dark-squared bishops,
Black would improve his strategic situation.} *

