{[%evp 0,32,30,-17,28,25,19,-14,13,-17,-10,-48,-9,-30,-11,-13,-2,4,4,4,11,-8,4,
12,7,6,10,-22,6,-24,-7,-1,20,20,-6]} 1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Bf5 5.
b3 {This used to be one of my favourite setups. I have obtained excellent
results by using it both with white and in the position with reversed colours
after 1.d4 Nf3 2.Nf3 g6 3.Bf4 (with black). However, Black should achieve
normal play with a bit of accuracy.} e6 6. Bb2 Nbd7 7. O-O Be7 ({The seemingly
more active} 7... Bd6 {exposes the bishop along the d-file.} 8. d3 O-O 9. Nbd2
Qe7 (9... h6 10. e4 $1 {leaves the bishop hanging on d6 in the event of
general exchanges on e4.}) 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. e4 dxe4 12. dxe4 Bxe4 (12... Nxe4
13. Nh4 Nxd2 14. Nxf5 exf5 15. Qxd2 Nc5 16. Rfe1 Ne6 17. Qd5 $14) 13. Nxe4 Nxe4
14. Nd4 {with strong initiative.}) 8. d3 (8. d4 {is inoffensive, since the
bishop is active now.} O-O 9. Nc3 h6 10. Nd2 {It is hard to indicate another
constructive plan.} b5 $5 {The most resolute way of fighting for space.} (10...
Re8 11. e4 dxe4 12. Ncxe4 Nxe4 13. Nxe4 Nf6 $11) 11. cxb5 (11. e4 dxe4 12.
Ndxe4 bxc4 13. bxc4 Rb8 $15) 11... cxb5 12. Nxb5 Qa5 13. Nc3 Rac8 14. e4 dxe4
15. Ndxe4 Nxe4 16. Nxe4 Rfd8 17. Qe2 Nf6 18. Rfd1 Nxe4 19. Bxe4 Bxe4 20. Qxe4
Rd5 21. Bc1 Rcd8 {½-½ Maitre,F (2363)-Delgado Ramos,H (2370) ICCF email 2018}
) 8... h6 9. Nbd2 O-O 10. a3 (10. Qc2 a5 11. a3 {is another possible move
order. By taking 10.a3 as the main line, I have maintained the possibility of
mentioning all White's plans as deviations on the next move.}) 10... a5 {
I remember the fascination provoked by seeing this tabiya on the chess set of
a teammate during my childhood. I did not understand much, but both sides'
flexible and patient approach strongly appealed to me. White will try to
prepare b3-b4, while also keeping an eye on e5. Achieving both is not easy,
though.} 11. Qc2 {The main continuation, planning Bc3 and b3-b4.} (11. Ra2 Bh7
{Now and in most other lines, Black is best advised to retreat with his bishop
at once, thus inviting White to show his cards.} 12. Qa1 {is a bit artificial.}
Re8 13. Ne5 (13. Rc1 Qb6 14. Bc3 {Iturrizaga Bonelli,E (2607)-Salgado Lopez,I 
(2584) chess24.com INT 2020 (½-½, 50)} c5 $1 $146 {Now is the moment to
confess that during my game with this system (or that with reversed colours) I
was permanently worried by this move (or, when playing black the reversed
position, c3-c4) in similar positions. Apparently, it wastes a tempo and
weakens the long light diagonal, but it fights against White's battery along
the dark diagonal.} 15. cxd5 exd5 16. d4 Rac8 $11 {/=/+ This is a favourable  
(for Black) version of the Isolani. The knight on d3 does not have access to
d4 and White's coordination is a bit artificial.}) 13... Bf8 14. Nxd7 (14. Ndf3
c5 $1 $146 {[%cal Ga5a4] The same issue.} 15. Nxd7 Nxd7 $15) 14... Nxd7 15. Bc3
Nc5 16. d4 (16. b4 Na4 $15) (16. Rc1 a4 17. b4 Nb3 18. Nxb3 axb3 19. Rb2 dxc4
20. dxc4 Bc2 $15) (16. Rb1 b5 17. cxb5 cxb5 18. Nf3 Rc8 19. Nd4 Qb6 20. b4 axb4
21. Bxb4 e5 22. Nb3 Na4 $11) 16... Na6 (16... Nd7 {½-½ Junge,K (2260)-Ehrke,
M (2242) Buesum 1999} 17. b4 {maintains some symbolic pressure.}) 17. e4 b5 18.
Rc1 Nc7 $15 {[%cal Ga5a4] With the unpleasant positional threat ...a5-a4,
undermining White's control on light squares.} 19. a4 b4 20. Bb2 f5 21. e5 f4 {
with excellent play. Most of White's pieces are passive.}) (11. Rc1 Bh7 12. Rc2
Re8 13. Qa1 {is a somewhat improved version of the previous line. It is also
more time consuming, though.} Bf8 14. Ne5 Qe7 15. Nxd7 Nxd7 16. Rfc1 f6 {
A typical plan in this system. Black prepares to recycle the bishop with ...
Kh8 and ...Bg8, followed by ...e6-e5.} 17. Bc3 (17. Nf1 $6 {Fuentes,M (2375)
-Gonzales, R (2290) Matanzas 1995 (½-½, 39) This plan takes the knight too
far from b3.} Kh8 18. Ne3 $6 Nc5 $1 19. Qa2 a4 $17) 17... Kh8 (17... Qxa3 18.
Ra2 Qd6 19. Bxa5 Kh8 $11 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gh7g8] followed by ...Bg8 and ...e6-e5.})
18. Ra2 Nb6 19. b4 axb4 20. axb4 e5 21. b5 Bg8 (21... cxb5 22. cxd5 b4 23. Bb2
Qd7 24. e4 Ra4 $13) 22. Ba5 Nd7 $11) (11. Bc3 {speeds up the queenside attack,
but obstructs the c-file too early.} Bh7 12. b4 axb4 13. axb4 Qc7 $1 {Since
White cannot set up pressure along the c-file, this move, preparing ...e6-e5,
solves Black's problems.} 14. Qb3 e5 15. Rxa8 Rxa8 16. Ra1 Rxa1+ 17. Bxa1 d4 $1
$146 (17... b5 {unnecesarily weakens c6.} 18. c5 d4 {1/2-1/2 (25) Kochyev,
A-Beliavsky,A (2555) Leningrad 1977} 19. Ne1 Bf5 20. Nc2 Be6 21. Qa3 Nd5 22.
Nf1 $14 {[%cal Ge2e3]}) 18. Bb2 Bf5 $11 {Black recycles his bishop, achieving
a good position.}) 11... Bh7 12. Bc3 ({The main alternative is} 12. Ne5 Re8 $1
(12... Nxe5 13. Bxe5 Nd7 14. Bc3 {gains a tempo for White}) 13. Nxd7 (13. Ndf3
Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Nd7 15. Nxd7 Qxd7 16. b4 {Gines Esteo,P (2483)-Nihal,S (2612)
Sitges 2019 (0-1, 52)} d4 (16... axb4 17. axb4 Bxb4 18. Rxa8 Rxa8 19. cxd5 exd5
20. Bxg7 Kxg7 21. Qb2+) 17. Rab1 axb4 18. axb4 e5 19. Bc1 Bf5 $15) 13... Nxd7
14. Bc3 b5 {One of the ways Black can meet the queenside attack.} 15. cxb5 cxb5
16. b4 axb4 17. axb4 Nb6 18. Rxa8 Qxa8 19. Bd4 Rc8 $11 20. Bc5 $6 {Ortega,L  
(2440)-Hoffman,A (2450) Nuoro 1993 (½-½, 34)} Nd7 21. Nb3 Nxc5 22. bxc5 (22.
Nxc5 Qa3 $15) 22... Bf6 $15 {[%cal Gb5b4,Gf6c3] followed by ...b5-b4 and ...
Bc3. The part played by the bishop on h7 is obvious. It pins the pawn on d3,
preventing d3-d4. The white queen cannot abandoin the light diagonal, since
this would run into ...Qa4 or ...Qa2.}) 12... Qc7 ({I prefer this to} 12... b5
{, which is playable, though.} 13. cxb5 cxb5 14. b4 axb4 ({A famous game,
showing White's possibilities in this system went} 14... Qc7 $6 {This move
offers White an essential tempo.} 15. Qb2 Nb6 (15... axb4 16. Bxb4 $1 $14) 16.
Be5 Qd7 17. Nb3 axb4 18. axb4 Rxa1 19. Rxa1 Na4 20. Qd2 $14 {Botvinnik,
M-Smyslov,V Moscow 1958 (1-0, 41)}) 15. axb4 Qc7 16. Qb2 Ra4 17. Rfc1 Qb6 $11)
13. Qb2 (13. cxd5 cxd5 $11) (13. b4 e5 $15 {Fivelstad,J (1854)-Bjornsson,T  
(2158) Reykjavik 2011 (½-½, 28)}) 13... c5 $1 {Once again, my dreaded move.
This time it is not new, having been played in several games.} 14. cxd5 (14. d4
dxc4 15. bxc4 (15. Nxc4 b5 16. Nce5 b4 $15) 15... Rfd8 16. d5 exd5 17. cxd5 Qb6
18. Qa2 Qa6 19. Rfe1 Ne4 $15) 14... exd5 15. Rfc1 (15. d4 b6 $15 {is similar
to the main line.}) 15... Qd6 $1 $146 {Removing the potential pin along the
c-file and renewing the threat ...d5-d4.} (15... b5 {Hesse,P (2420)-Szabo,J
Varna 1979 (1-0, 57)} 16. b4 axb4 17. axb4 c4 $14) (15... Rfe8 16. e4 (16. b4
b6 {1/2-1/2 (63) Yarmolyuk,Y-Buzas,G LSS email 2007}) 16... dxe4 17. dxe4 b5
18. Bf1 Qb7 19. e5 b4 20. axb4 axb4 21. Rxa8 Qxa8 22. exf6 bxc3 23. Qxc3 Bxf6
24. Qc4 $11) (15... d4 $2 16. Bxd4) 16. d4 (16. e4 $2 d4) 16... b6 $15 {
Once again, the passive knight on d2 yields Black a comfortable version of the
hanging pawns. His bishop is more active on h7 than it would be on b7, where
it would stay in the Queen's Indian, for instance.} *

