1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Bf5 5. d4 {I have played this system in
many games over the internet, during the long months of lockdown. Despite my
good results, I do not find it too challenging. These were just 3 + 2 online
blitz games...} e6 ({Pawn grabbing is almost suicidal.} 5... Bxb1 $2 6. Rxb1
Qa5+ $2 7. Bd2 Qxa2 8. Ra1 Qxc4 (8... Qxb2 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. O-O Nc6 11. Qa4 $18
) 9. Ra5 e6 10. O-O $1 (10. b3 Qb4 $1) 10... Bb4 11. b3 Bxd2 12. bxc4 Bxa5 13.
Qb3 $18) 6. Nc3 h6 7. O-O ({My usual move order against any black 6th move was
} 7. Qb3 Qb6 8. c5 Qxb3 ({One of the main ideas behind this move order is that
the relatively desirable} 8... Qa6 $2 {runs into} 9. Bf1 $1 b5 10. a4 $16 {
This resource is not available after White has castled.}) (8... Qc7 9. Bf4 Qc8
$14 {is solid but a bit passive.}) 9. axb3 Na6 $1 {Preventing or at least
delaying the advance of the b-pawn.} (9... Nbd7 10. b4 a6 11. b5 $14) 10. Ne5 (
10. Ra4 Nd7 11. O-O Be7 12. h4 e5 13. Be3 e4 14. Nd2 Nc7 15. b4 a6 $15 {
Li,X (2328)-Tan,Z (2510) Xinghua 2021 (0-1, 29)}) (10. Bf4 g5 $146 11. Be5 Be7
12. O-O O-O $15 {[%cal Gf6d7]}) 10... Nb4 11. O-O (11. Ra4 a5) 11... Nd7 12.
Nxd7 Kxd7 13. Ra4 a5 14. Bd2 Be7 15. Na2 (15. e4 Bh7 16. f3 Rhb8 17. Rfa1 Nc2
18. Rc1 Nb4 $11) 15... Nxa2 16. Rxa2 Bc2 17. Rfa1 b6 18. cxb6 (18. b4 a4 $15)
18... Rhb8 19. Rxa5 (19. Bxa5 Bxb3 $19) 19... Rxa5 20. Rxa5 (20. Bxa5 Bxb3 21.
e3 Ra8 {[%cal Gd7c8,Gc8b7]} 22. b7 Rb8 $11) 20... Rxb6 21. Ra7+ Ke8 $11) 7...
Nbd7 8. Qb3 ({The familiar} 8. Nd2 Be7 9. e4 dxe4 10. Ndxe4 Nxe4 11. Nxe4 O-O {
yields Black a comfortable version of the Caro Kann.} 12. Be3 Nf6 13. Nc3 Rc8
$5 {An interesting move, preparing the promising pawn sacrifice ...b7-b5,
fighting for the light squares.} (13... Qa5 14. a3 Rfd8 15. b4 Qa6 16. Qb3 Ng4
17. a4 Bd3 18. c5 Qc4 $11) 14. Qb3 (14. a3 b5 $11 15. cxb5 cxb5 16. Nxb5 $2 Qb6
17. a4 Ng4 $15) (14. Re1 b5 $11) (14. Qe2 Ng4 15. Rad1 Nxe3 16. fxe3 Bg6 $11
17. c5 {Bosnjak,N (2117)-Mrkonjic,N (2362) Bosnjaci 2016 (0-1, 46)} b6 18. b4
bxc5 19. bxc5 e5 $11) 14... Ng4 $1 $146 15. Qxb7 Nxe3 16. fxe3 Bg5 17. Rfe1 c5
$44) 8... Qb6 9. c5 Qxb3 (9... Qa6 10. Nd2 b6 11. e4 dxe4 12. Ndxe4 bxc5 13.
Nxf6+ gxf6 14. dxc5 $44) 10. axb3 a6 {AFter having developed the queen's
knight, Black is in time to get rid of the pin along the a-file.} 11. b4 O-O-O
$5 {An ambitious move. Black uses his king for protecting his queenside,
anticipating the knight's transfer from f3 all the way to a5.} (11... Rc8 {
is playable, though.}) 12. Bf4 {White has to use his attacking chances.
Otherwise, Black would get active play with ...g7-g5, followed by ...Bg7 and
later ...e6-e5.} (12. b5 $5 {leads to sharp play, too.} cxb5 13. Nxb5 axb5 14.
Bf4 Nb8 15. Ra8 Kd7 16. Bxb8 (16. Rxb8 Rxb8 17. Bxb8 Bxc5 $17) 16... Bd6 17.
Bxd6 Rxa8 18. Ne5+ Ke8 19. f3 Nd7 20. e4 Nxe5 21. Bxe5 f6 22. Bd6 Bg6 23. exd5
exd5 24. Re1+ Kd8 25. Re7 {White is very active and has entirely adequate
compensation for the exchange. Black maintains the equality by activating his
rooks.} Re8 26. Rxb7 Bd3 27. h4 Re2 {[%cal Ge2c2,Ga8a1]} 28. Rxg7 Ra1+ 29. Kh2
Rc1 30. g4 Rcc2 31. Kh3 b4 32. h5 b3 33. Rb7 Rxg2 34. Rb8+ Kd7 35. Rb7+ Ke8 36.
Rb8+ Kf7 37. Rb7+ {drawn}) 12... g5 13. Be5 Be7 14. b5 cxb5 15. Rfc1 (15. Nxb5
Nxe5 16. Nxe5 axb5 $17) 15... g4 16. Nxb5 Nxe5 17. Nxe5 axb5 18. c6 Kc7 19.
cxb7+ Kxb7 20. Ra5 {Being a piece down, White has to play for a perpetual now.}
Rb8 21. Rc6 (21. Rxb5+ Ka6 $19) 21... Bb4 22. Raa6 (22. Rxb5+ Ka7 23. Rxb8 Rxb8
24. Rc7+ Ka6 25. Bf1 Ne4 $17) 22... Ra8 23. Rab6+ {drawn} *

