{[%evp 0,46,19,-32,-23,-4,-27,-20,-16,-25,-16,-20,-6,-12,4,11,4,18,6,2,29,20,
19,-10,-11,-13,1,-3,6,-2,11,11,32,34,35,39,33,41,37,37,23,43,24,15,13,41,21,0,
0]} 1. b3 {Previously, this was considered a sideline that did not require a
lot of attention. However, with more and more games played at the top level,
it proved to hold some poison if Black is not careful with the plans or
specific move orders. The opening has been on the rise with numerous strong
players often employing it in rapid and blitz- e.g. Carlsen, Nakamura,
Nepomniachtchi etc. The main idea of starting with this move is to get a fresh
position with complicated middlegame play and, at the same time, avoid long
theoretical battles. Nevertheless, if Black is familiar with a few subtleties,
he should get excellent chances.} d5 {I believe this to be the best response.
Black has several good systems though, and it is a matter of style to choose
one} ({For example, if you are a King's Indian Defense fan, there is nothing
wrong with} 1... Nf6 2. Bb2 g6) ({If you are a 1.e4 player, you might find the
} 1... e5 {positions to your liking}) 2. Bb2 {Black has a couple of different
options to choose from- the most popular ones are 2...Nf6, 2...Bg4, 2...Bf5.
To put it briefly, 2...Bg4 results in lively double-edged positions, 2...Bf5
is a bit inaccurate in my opinion, and the most solid personal favourite of
mine is 2. ..Nf6. By playing 2...Nf6, Black waits for White to dedicate to a
setup and only then puts Bf5 if appropriate.} Nf6 {[%cal Rc8f5]} (2... Bg4 {
also leads to interesting positions where Black has proved to be fine. The
move is designed to create problems for White to play 3.e3 or 3.Nf3. White has
several ways to react:} 3. f3 {engaging in concrete dynamic play early on.
Both the f5 and h5 retreats work for Black} (3. h3 {In my opinion, this can
only be troublesome for White} Bh5 4. g4 Bg6 5. Bg2 h5 {Black immediately
starts counterplay and undermines the White pawns} 6. g5 e5 $1 {[%cal Rd8g5]}
7. Bxe5 Nc6 $15 {Gaining tempi to develop as White cannot protect the pawn} 8.
Bf4 Nd4 {[%cal Rd4c2]} 9. d3 Ne6 10. Bc1 (10. Qd2 Nxf4 11. Qxf4 Bd6 12. Qd2 c6
13. h4 Ne7 14. Nf3 O-O $17 {[%cal Rf8e8,Re7f5]}) 10... Nxg5 $17 {White's pawn
structure is disastrous. Over the next couple of moves, Black is going to
complete his development and start exploiting the semi-open e file.}) (3. Nf3 {
Black is faced with a choice: either take the knight changing the pawn
structure or keep the light-squared bishop} Nd7 (3... Bxf3 {transforms into
the Trompowsky with colours reversed} 4. exf3 (4. gxf3 e6 5. e3 Nc6 {[%cal
Rc2c4,Rd5d4]} 6. f4 (6. Bb5 Nge7 $11) 6... Nh6 {[%cal Rh6f5,Rd5d4]}) 4... e6 5.
f4 Nf6 6. g3 h5 7. h4 g6 8. Bg2 Bg7 9. d3 c5 10. Nd2 Nc6 11. O-O (11. Nf3 Qa5+)
11... O-O 12. Re1 Ng4 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Nf3 Qa5 $15 {[%csl Rc3,Rg2][%cal Ra5c3]
}) 4. e3 e6 5. c4 Ngf6 6. h3 Bh5 7. Be2 c6 8. O-O Bd6 9. d4 O-O 10. Nbd2 a5 11.
a3 Qe7 {A standard position. Black has harmoniously developed pieces and, I
believe, a small but edge in a practical game} 12. Ne5 {[%cal Yd3h7,Ye2d3,
Yd1c2] Playing Bb2 with the idea to organize a kingside attack after jumping
Ne5, is only dangerous if White has also the light-squared bishop and the
queen aimed at the Black king} (12. Qc2 {If White decides to take a slower
approach, Black will start pushing in the centre :} e5 13. dxe5 (13. cxd5 e4 {
[%csl Re2][%cal Yh5e2] Be2 is unprotected}) 13... Nxe5 14. Rfc1 Rfe8 15. Nxe5
Bxe2 16. Ndf3 Bxf3 17. Nxf3 dxc4 18. Qxc4 $11 {After all the exchanges,
Black's position is more than fine. He has a nice control over the centre and
3 vs 2 pawns on the queenside. Additionally, he has the a3 pawn targetted and
White needs to dedicate resources to its protection} Rad8 19. Nd4 Be5 {[%cal
Yf6e4,Yg7g6]}) 12... Bxe2 13. Qxe2 Rfd8 14. Rfd1 (14. e4 Bxe5 15. dxe5 Nxe4 16.
Nxe4 dxe4 17. Qxe4 Nc5 18. Qc2 Qg5 19. Rad1 Qf5 {[%csl Rb3,Rd3][%cal Rf5d3]}
20. Qxf5 exf5 $15 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Rc5b3,Rc5e6]}) 14... Bc7 $11 {[%csl Re5]
[%cal Rd7e5] Black retreats the Bishop and is now ready to take on e5. Black
can afford to exchange that knight and let White have a strong pawn on e5
since Black does not have a light-squared bishop to start an attack} 15. Ndf3 (
15. f4 a4 {Fixating more of White's pawns on dark squares. In the future,
Black wants to trade his B and N for White's knights, thus reaching a strong N
vs bad B endgame.} 16. b4 dxc4 17. Ndxc4 Nd5 {[%csl Ra3,Rb2,Rb4,Rd4,Re3,Rf4]}
18. g3 f5 {[%csl Rb2,Gd5,Ge4]} 19. Kg2 g5 $15 {White's dark-squared bishop is
blocked so Black can build up a kingside attack after Kh8, Rg8}) 15... a4 {
typical idea} 16. b4 Ne4 {[%cal Rf7f6] Black is ready to evict the White knight
} 17. Rac1 Nd6 {provoking yet another weakening of the light squares} 18. c5
Nxe5 19. Nxe5 (19. cxd6 Nxf3+ $19) 19... Nb5 $15 {[%csl Rb2,Rc7][%cal Rf7f6,
Re6e5] The knight is perfectly placed attacking both the a3 and d4 pawns.
Meanwhile, White's dark-squared bishop is stuck with no prospects of coming
back into the game. White can do nothing but watch how his opponent slowly
advances his central pawns gaining space}) 3... Bf5 {is more to my taste. The
move is tricky but less popular for some reason} (3... Bh5 4. h4 {seizing
space and aiming to trap the bishop} f6 {opening an escape route for Bh5} (4...
f5 $5 {is a viable alternative tested by GM Shirov. I consider it to be worth
checking out as well}) 5. d4 {White stops e5 and fights for the centre} (5. g4
Bf7 {[%cal Re7e5]} 6. d4 e5 7. dxe5 fxe5 8. Bxe5 Nc6 9. Bb2 Bb4+ 10. Nd2 Nf6
$17 {[%csl Re3,Rf2,Rf4,Rg3] Black is way ahead in development in exchange for
the sacrificed pawn}) (5. Nh3 e5 $15) 5... e6 {the standard continuation.
However, I also analyzed a more direct way of play:} (5... e5 6. dxe5 (6. Nc3
Bb4 7. e3 (7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. Bxc3 Nc6 9. e3 Qd6 {[%cal Re5d4,Rd6g3]} 10. Nh3 (10.
Ne2 O-O-O 11. Qd2 Bf7 12. Bb2 h5 13. O-O-O Nge7 14. g3 Kb8 15. Bh3 Rhe8 $11)
10... O-O-O) 7... Ne7 8. Nge2 c5 9. a3 Bxc3+ 10. Bxc3 Nd7 11. Qd2 Bf7 12. O-O-O
O-O $11 {[%cal Ra7a5,Rb6b5]}) 6... fxe5 7. Bxe5 Nc6 8. Bb2 Nf6 $17 {Black's
compensation is fantastic and I find his chances preferable}) 6. Nc3 Bd6 7. Nh3
$14) 4. e4 {a gambit idea White typically goes for.} (4. f4 {transposes to
another standard line:} Nf6 5. Nf3 h6 {securing a place for the bishop} 6. e3
e6 7. Be2 Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. d3 c5 {The position resembles a reversed version
of the Leningrad variation in the Dutch Defense} 10. Ne5 (10. Nbd2 $2 Ng4)
10... Nfd7 $15 {taking measures against the strong Ne5} ({The reason Black
exchanges Nf6 and not Nb8, is that after taking on e5, he does not want to
lose a tempo:} 10... Nbd7 11. Nd2 Nxe5 12. fxe5 {[%cal Ye5f6]}) 11. Nd2 Nxe5
12. Bxe5 (12. fxe5 {[%csl Re5][%cal Rb2e5] is strategically bad} Bg5 $17) 12...
Nc6 13. Bb2 Bf6 $17 {Black neutralizes White's most active piece}) (4. e3 e6)
4... dxe4 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. g4 (6. Qe2 {is inaccurate since White is not able to
push g4 anymore} exf3 7. Nxf3 Nc6 8. O-O-O e6 9. d3 Bc5 $17 {In my opinion, it
is not clear where White's compensation for the pawn lies so Black has nothing
to fear}) 6... Bg6 7. Qe2 (7. h4 $6 Qd6 {[%cal Rd6g3]} 8. Nh3 Qg3+ 9. Nf2 exf3
10. h5 Nxg4 $19) 7... Nc6 8. O-O-O e5 {is my preferred course of action} 9.
fxe4 {is not recommended: White's pieces are passive and his pawn structure is
dubious} (9. g5 Nd5 $15 {[%cal Rd5f4]}) (9. h4 {The most natural. However,
Black is prepared and already has everything under control} Nd4 10. Qg2 h5 11.
g5 Nd5 12. fxe4 Nf4 $17 {Black occupied all the important central squares} 13.
Qg3 Bd6 14. Kb1 (14. Nh3 Bxe4 {[%csl Rc1,Rg3][%cal Rf4e2,Rd4e2]}) 14... O-O {
The kingside is blocked so Black's king is not in danger on g8} 15. Nh3 Nfe6
$17 {[%cal Rc7c6,Ra7a4,Rb7b5]})) (2... Bf5 {At first glance, it seems like it
does not matter if Black plays Bf5 or Nf6 first. However, that is not true- if
the bishop is developed first, White has the opportunity to choose a setup
that restricts it early on} 3. g3 e6 4. Bg2 Nf6 5. d3 h6 6. Nd2 Bh7 {White has
delayed the development of Ng1 and can play e4 very fast} 7. e4 Be7 8. Nh3 O-O
9. O-O c5 (9... a5 10. a3 c5 11. a4 Nc6 12. exd5 exd5 13. Nf4 {[%csl Rd5]} d4
$6 14. Re1 $16 Bd6 15. Nh5 Nxh5 16. Qxh5 Qc7 17. Nc4 b6 (17... Bg6 18. Qf3 Rfd8
19. Re2 {[%cal Ra1e1]}) 18. Qd5) 10. exd5 {has been played by Indian superstar
Nihal Sarin} (10. f4 $13 {[%cal Rh3f2,Rg3g4,Rf4f5] creates a mess on the board.
Even though the engine says Black's position is stable enough, I do not share
its opinion- it is easier to play as White as he is the one dictating the
course of the game}) 10... exd5 11. Nf4 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Rb2f6] Emphasizing
the weakness on d5. Sooner or later, White will initiate mass exchanges of the
minor pieces aiming for a position where Black is only left with his isolated
light-squared bishop} Nc6 {[%csl Rc2,Rd3,Rd5,Rh7]} 12. Re1 {Black's position
is already tough, for example:} Re8 $2 13. Bxf6 $16 Bxf6 14. Rxe8+ Qxe8 15. Rb1
{Black is forced to give up the light squares in the centre} d4 16. Nd5 Bd8 17.
b4 {[%csl Rd8,Rh7][%cal Yd2c4,Yc4d6,Yb1b7,Yg2b7] White controls the centre and
has a fantastic play on the queenside whereas Black's pieces are uncoordinated
and awkward}) 3. Nf3 {Now is the appropriate time to develop the bishop} (3. e3
Bf5) (3. f4 Bf5 (3... g6 {is the most played option where Black scores great}
4. Nf3 Bg7 5. g3 O-O 6. Bg2 c5 7. O-O Nc6 8. e3 (8. Ne5 Bd7 9. e3 Rc8 10. d3
Nxe5 11. Bxe5 Ng4) 8... d4 $15) 4. Nf3 h6 5. e3 e6 {and so on}) (3. g3 c5 {
is Black's best reaction in my opinion} (3... g6) 4. Bg2 Nc6 5. Nf3 (5. f4 g6
6. Nf3 Bg7 7. O-O O-O $15) 5... Qc7 {[%cal Re7e5] preventing Ne5 and preparing
e5} 6. d4 (6. O-O e5 {Black gets a firm grip of the centre} 7. d3 Be7 8. Nbd2
O-O 9. e4 d4 $15 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Yf6e8,Ye8d6] the dark-squared bishop has no
place on b2}) 6... cxd4 7. Nxd4 e5 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. O-O Be6 {The position
resembles a Grunfeld structure with colours reversed. However, White has lost
