h5 {a choice for players with a more aggressive style}) 11. c4 (11. e3 Bd6 12.
c4 O-O 13. Rc1 Qe7) 11... d4 $15 {[%cal Yc6c5,Yf8e7,Ye8g8]}) (3. Bxf6 {Giving
up the bishop only leaves White in a slightly worse position. By comparison
with the Trompowsky, b3 has weakened the dark squares whereas in the usual
line White sets up his pawn structure to control them. Black can take either
way although exf6 as feels more natural to me} exf6 $15 {[%csl Rb2,Rc3]}) 3...
Bf5 4. g3 (4. e3 {[%cal Ye7e6,Yc7c6,Yh7h6,Yb8d7,Yf8d6,Ye8g8] Whenever Black is
faced with e3, he wants to build a London system setup} h6 (4... e6 5. Nh4) 5.
c4 e6 6. Nc3 (6. Be2 c6 7. O-O Nbd7 8. d4 Bd6 9. Nbd2 O-O 10. Ne5 Qe7 11. f4 (
11. Ndf3 Rfd8 {[%cal Rf6e4]}) 11... a5 12. a3 Ne4 $15) 6... c6 7. d4 Nbd7 8.
Be2 (8. Bd3 Bb4 {[%csl Rc3,Re4]} 9. Bxf5 (9. O-O O-O) (9. a3 {is in Black's
favor} Bd6) 9... exf5 10. O-O O-O 11. cxd5 Bxc3 12. Bxc3 Nxd5 $15 {Black's
light-squared strategy has tremendously paid off and given him complete
control of the center} 13. Bb2 Qe7 14. Re1 {stopping f4} (14. Rc1 f4) 14... Qe6
15. Rc1 a5 16. a3 {the inclusion of this move almost always favors Black as it
is a potential weakness} Rfe8 17. Qd3 a4 18. b4 b5 {[%csl Rc4]} 19. Rc2 N5b6 {
[%csl Rb2] The difference in strength between the black knight and the white
bishop is clear}) 8... Bd6 9. O-O O-O $11 {[%cal Yd8e7,Yf8e8,Ya8d8,Ye6e5]})
4... e6 5. Bg2 h6 6. O-O Be7 {The precise move. In case of Nbd7 or Bd6, White
can switch to a plan with fast e4 and create problems for his opponent} 7. d3
O-O 8. c4 c6 9. Nbd2 Bh7 {Typical prophylaxis so that e4 does not come with a
tempo} 10. a3 a5 {White has 2 main plans:} 11. Ra2 (11. Qc2 Nbd7 12. e4 (12.
Rac1 Bd6 {opens up the e7 square for the queen from where it would eye the a3
pawn and support e5} 13. Qb1 Qe7 14. Qa1 e5) 12... Nc5 $15 {[%csl Rd3,Re4,Rh7]
addresses all the weaknesses in White's camp}) 11... Nbd7 12. Qa1 Bd6 {[%cal
Rd8e7,Re6e5]} (12... Re8 {[%cal Re7d6] is an alternative where Black retreats
the bishop to protect the king and prepares e5} 13. Ne5 Bf8 {[%cal Rd7e5,Rf6d7]
} 14. Ndf3 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Nd7 16. Nxd7 Qxd7 $15 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Rf8g7,Re6e5,
Rf7f6]}) 13. e4 dxe4 {White is at a crossroad but only one of the moves is
good!} 14. Nxe4 ({Former World championship challenger Sergey Karjakin chose
the somewhat suspicious} 14. dxe4 $6 {where after} Be7 15. e5 (15. Rd1 Qc7)
15... Ne4 $17 {[%csl Ra2,Rb2,Rb7,Rc6,Rg2] White is in trouble}) 14... Nxe4 (
14... Be7 {is the safer choice. White has nothing better than:} 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6
16. Bxf6 Qxf6 17. d4 Be4 {Activating the bishop and putting pressure on
White's center} 18. Qc3 Bxf3 19. Bxf3 e5 20. d5 (20. dxe5 Nxe5 {Black's knight
has control of the dark squares whereas the White bishop is restricted by the
b7-c6 pawn chain} 21. Bg2 Rfd8 {[%csl Rb7,Rc6,Rg2]}) 20... e4 $1 {wins a pawn
for Black} 21. Qxf6 Nxf6 22. Bg2 cxd5 23. cxd5 Nxd5 24. Bxe4 $4 Nc3 $19) 15.
dxe4 e5 {Sacrificing a pawn for the initiative! Activity is worth more than
material!} 16. Nxe5 (16. Rd1 Qe7 $15 {[%csl Rb3,Re4][%cal Yd7c5]}) 16... Nxe5
17. Bxe5 Bxe5 18. Qxe5 Re8 19. Qf4 Qb6 {[%cal Rb6b3]} (19... Qd3 20. Rb2 Rad8 (
