-105,-86,-111,-466,-466,-747,-1373,-1072,-1249,-1452,-1571,-1571,-1528]} 1. Nf3
d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. b3 Bf5 4. Bb2 h6 5. c4 e6 6. Be2 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Nc3 c6 9. h3
Nbd7 10. d3 Bh7 11. Re1 {In my opinion, White did not play very precisely and
did not get anything from the opening} Re8 (11... e5) 12. Rc1 a6 {
Overprotecting b5} 13. Bf1 e5 $15 14. cxd5 cxd5 15. d4 e4 16. Ne5 Bd6 (16...
Bb4 {is better because it provokes the creation of the a3 weakness} 17. a3 Bd6
{[%csl Ra3,Rb3]}) 17. Nxd7 Qxd7 18. Na4 Rad8 19. Nc5 Qe7 20. Rc2 {Looks to
build up an initiative on the queenside but, in fact, White does not have real
threats!} Bf5 $19 {Black activates his only poorly placed piece and starts
counterplay on the kingside} 21. a4 g5 {[%cal Yg5g4] A typical idea to open up
lines against the enemy king after White's h3. The majority of White's pieces
are isolated on the other side of the board and will be of no help to their
monarch} (21... Bb8 {[%cal Re7d6] is worth considering as well} 22. Ba3 Nh7 {
[%csl Ra3]} 23. Qc1 Ng5 {Black aims all his forces at the white king} 24. Nxa6
{demonstrates how rapidly Black's attack becomes decisive} (24. Kh1 Qd6 25. g3
Qg6 26. h4 Nf3 $19 {[%csl Rb8,Rf3,Rf5,Rg6,Rh1]}) 24... Nxh3+ 25. gxh3 Qg5+ 26.
Kh1 bxa6 $19 {[%csl Rh1,Rh3]}) 22. a5 g4 23. hxg4 Nxg4 {White's position
collapses} 24. f3 exf3 25. Qxf3 Bh2+ 26. Kh1 Qh4 27. g3 Bxg3+ 28. Kg1 Bxc2 0-1

