[%cal Re6e5]} (17... Ng4 18. Qc3 Nf6 19. cxd5 Nxd5 20. Qb2 e5 $11) 18. cxd5
Nxd5 {The correct recapture once White relieves the tension in the center} (
18... exd5 $6 {is a mistake a lot of people make. White can follow up with b4,
Nd4 and achieve excellent counterplay against the b7 and c6 pawns} 19. Qxe7
Rxe7 20. b4 $16) 19. Nd2 f6 20. Qb2 e5 21. Nc4 e4 22. dxe4 Bxe4 23. Bxe4 Qxe4
24. Qc2 {[%csl Ra5,Rb6]} Ra8 25. Qxe4 Rxe4 26. f3 Rd4 27. Kf2 a4 $11) 13...
dxe4 14. dxe4 (14. Nxe4 {is the correct way for White to go} Be7 (14... Nxe4
15. dxe4 e5 $5)) 14... e5 (14... Be7 $17 {is the refutation}) 15. Nxe5 Bxe5 16.
Bxe5 Nxe5 17. Qxe5 Re8 18. Qf4 Qd4 (18... Nd7 {[%cal Rd7c5,Rc5d3,Rd8e7]}) 19.
Re1 Rad8 20. h4 (20. Nf3 Qc3 21. e5 a4 22. b4 Nd7 23. h4 $11) 20... Re7 {
Black is prepared to double the rooks on either file} 21. Qe3 Ng4 22. Qxd4 Rxd4
23. f3 Ne5 24. a4 (24. f4 Nd3 25. Re3 Red7 26. Nf3 Rxe4) 24... Nd3 25. Re3 Nc5
({Black could have obtained a better position with} 25... f5 $15) 26. g4 f5 27.
gxf5 Bxf5 28. Bf1 Bg6 29. Kf2 Ne6 (29... Rf7 $15 {[%csl Re4,Rf3]} 30. Kg2 Rfd7
