{The current lecture features the variation} 1. c4 c6 2. e4 d5 {More often,
this position arises in the Caro-Kann Defence after 1.e4 c6 2.c4. Therefore,
the current material will be very useful both for Caro-Kann and Slav players.
In almost all the variations, Black will be playing against an Isolated
Queen's Pawn (IQP). Therefore, at the beginning of the lecture I provide model
games featuring this important pawn structure. In my opinion, White's most
challenging follow up is} 3. exd5 cxd5 4. d4 {leading to the so-called Panov
Attack.} ({I also cover the positions arising after} 4. cxd5 Nf6 {[%cal Gb1c3,
Gf1b5,Gd1a4] This is an important branching point. Now, I deal with three main
continuations: 5.Qa4+, 5.Bb5+, and 5.Nc3. In all the cases, Black's approach
will be pretty much the same. Therefore, I think that my suggested repertoire
will be very practical.}) {The first important crossroads in the Panov Attack
is being reached after} 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 {Now, the main line is} 6. Nf3 ({
I also examine the ambitious} 6. Bg5) {Against the main line, I would like to
suggest the rare} 6... a6 $5 {Black usually plays 6...Bg4 or 6...e6. Even
though he does not face problems in the main lines, my idea was to provide a
practical, reliable and easy to learn repertoire. The system with 6...a6
covers all these requirements. There is almost nothing to memorize. The good
understanding of the positions with IQP will be more than enough to play this
line.} *

