these games because our entire repertoire is based on positions with IQP.}  *

[Event "Moscow-ch 17th"]
[Site "Moscow "]
[Date "1937.11.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Belavenets, Sergey Vesevolodovi"]
[Black "Rauzer, Vsevolod"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Annotator "GM Grigor Grigorov"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "6k1/p2b1p1p/1p4p1/1N1p4/8/P3P3/1P3PPP/6K1 w - - 0 1"]
[PlyCount "61"]
[EventDate "1937.11.??"]
[EventRounds "17"]
[EventCountry "URS"]
[SourceVersionDate "2009.09.29"]

{A well-known rule is that the defending resources are bigger than the one for
the attacks. This guideline also concerns the positions with an isolated pawn.
When the opponent manages to rebound from our attack on the kingside, our
spatial advantage loses its value and the isolated pawn becomes a weakness.
You have to remember that every exchange of the pieces brings us closer to the
endgame, where the isolator is extremely vulnerable. Unlike the middlegame
positions, in which our main goal is to prevent the movement of the pawn 
(usually by blocking it with a knight), in the final stage of the game, we try
to win it. According to a famous saying of the Chinese philosopher Lao Tzu,
the one who does not know where it goes, necessarily arrive somewhere else. In
this frame of mind, I would like to analyze the game against an isolated pawn,
proceeding from the fundamental aim - the winning of the pawn. This
retrospective approach has to start from the endgame and only then, we can
deepen our past understandings of middlegame positions. The following example
has a very special role in the formation of my chess knowledge. The position
in the diagram has been reached in the game between Belavenets - Rauzer played
in 1937. I was still a child when I first saw this example on the pages of one
of my favourite chess books "Endgame Strategy", whose author is the famous
chess player and teacher Mikhail Shereshevski. This endgame impressed me not
only with its instructive view on the isolated pawn but also with the fact
that it comprises endgame fundamental principles. Now, we will try to assess
the occurred position. It is obvious, that due to the current nature of the
position (endgame), the isolated queen pawn in the Black's field is a weakness
that has to be protected. In addition, the White's pawn structure is compact
and Black has no chance to create any counterplay - he is doomed to passive
defence. On the other hand, besides the isolated pawn, Black has other
weaknesses as well. As we know from the principle of two weaknesses, in order
to realize a position with advantage, there have to be at least two weaknesses
in the opposing camp. In the light of the above-mentioned findings, we can
build the following strategy for the game: 1) to put maximum pressure on the
isolated pawn on "d5". For this purpose, the white king has to take the
blocking position on "d4" and the knight to attack the pawn on "c3"; 2) to
grasp the space on the queenside in order to fix the opponent's pawns which in
the future may become objects of attack; 3) pawn attack on the kingside, which
aim is to create the second weakness in Black's field; 4) combined attack on
the opponent's weaknesses and winning one of them. Now, let us see how the
soviet master Sergey Belavenets puts in action our plan.} 1. Nc3 $1 {Based on
the articles of GM Viktor Gavrikov, we are acquainted with the idea of placing
the knight on "d4". As already notices, the blockade of the isolated pawn with
a knight is characteristic of the middlegame positions, where the main idea is
to reduce the opponent's attacking ideas related to the movement of the pawn.
When there are still many pieces on the board, it is not enough just to
control the square that is in front of the isolated pawn. In these situations,
very often, the opponent sacrifices the central pawn in order to activate the
pieces. The things are absolutely different in the endgame. As at this stage
of the game, the sacrifice of the isolator does not endanger, the control of
the square in front of it is enough. As already mentioned, in the middlegame
the aim is to block the isolated pawn, while in the endgame, it is to destroy
it.} Bc6 {Maybe it is a better place for the bishop. From "c6", it indirectly
places pressure on the long diagonal and especially on the "g2" pawn. In these
circumstances, White has to decide how to place his pawns on the kingside
before the kind is going to "d4". In addition, from this position, the bishop
also controls the "b5" square, where in some cases the white knight might be
placed.]} ({Another possible try is} 1... Be6 {. but in that case, Black will
be deprived of any chances of a counter play.}) 2. Kf1 Kf8 3. f3 $1 {Diagram 
[#] A key move for White's strategy! Remember that in cases when the
light-squared bishop of the opponent is placed on the "h1-a8" diagonal, the
"g2-f3" pawn structure substantively diminishes its activity. In general, in
the position with a strong knight against a weak bishop, the side playing with
the knight places the pawns on the colour of the bishop. We have to make sure
that the pawns are placed correctly in order for them not to become objects of
attack.} ({A mistake is} 3. Ke2 $2 {,because the "g2" pawn remains unprotected.
Black can create a counter play by 3...d4} d4 $132 {[%csl Rg2][%cal Gc6g2]}) ({
The move} 3. g3 {prevents the tactical opportunities related to the d5-d4
breakthrough, but weakens the white squares on the kingside, which allows for
possible activation of the bishop.}) 3... Ke7 4. Ke2 Ke6 5. Kd3 Ke5 $1 {
Diagram [#] Black does everything possible in order to impede the
centralization of the white king. It is obvious, that in order to place the
king on "d4", it is necessary for White to repel the black king by f3-f4. Thus,
the white pawns on the kingside will not be optimally positioned, because it
would weaken the complex of white squares. However, Black's position remains
extremely passive and this slight structural imperfection cannot change the
turn of the game.} 6. f4+ Ke6 7. Kd4 $14 {[%csl Gc3,Rc6,Gd4,Rd5] Diagram [#]
The first part of the plan is done. Now, the black pieces are chained to the
isolated pawn and have the role of passive observers. However, the "d5" pawn
is the only weakness in Black's position and White has no more resources to
increase the pressure on it. Thus, eventually, White will have to create the
second weakness on the kingside. Here is the moment to focus on one of the
main rules found in every textbook on endgames. The rule says: when the
opponent is deprived of counterplay, there is no need to rush with the
implementation of the preliminary set plan. To sudden actions, we proceed when
the position is already enhanced to the limit. Now, we will analyse the
position on the diagram in light of the above-mentioned rule. A closer look,
we will find that we can significantly strengthen our position on the
queenside. This can be achieved by the means of the following idea: b2-b4-b5
followed by Na2-b4. Thus fulfilling four main objectives: 1) to conquer space
on the queenside 2) to limit the activity of the black light-squared bishop 3)
to activate the knight 4) to fix the pawn on "a7", which may become the
subject of attacks. It is therefore important not to take quick decisions in
the endgame.} Kd6 8. b4 Ke6 {Black totally adopts the passive strategy, he
only can wait. Despite the lack of opportunity for particular counterplay, he
should seek to strengthen his position. It is clear that White's long-term
plan predicts the movement of the pawns on the kingside, aiming to create an
additional weakness. Considering White's plan, it is possible to consider
fixing the "h7" pawn through g2-g4-g5 followed by Ne2-g3 and h2-h4-h5-h6. In
the case of such a structure, the relocation of the knight on "f6" would play
a crucial role. If Black decides to move the "f" pawn, the eventual sacrifice
on the knight on "g6" is very dangerous. As the readers already understood, in
this type of position, the calculations of the different variations might help
a lot. Each of the opponents, based on their own strategical knowledge, seeks
to draw a clear picture of the best position for his pieces, in his head.} ({
Due to similar reasons cited by me, a modern endgame expert might prefer} 8...
h5 {In this position, White can again prepare the movement of "g" pawn to "g5".
However, in such a scenario, there are two important differences that should
be considered: 1) allowing the pawn exchange on "g4" that is always beneficial
for the party defending itself; 2) White will fix the "f7" pawn that is closer
to the black king, thus, can be easily protected.}) 9. b5 Bb7 ({The black
bishop cannot be relocated on the "c8-h3" diagonal through} 9... Bd7 $2 {
, because White easily wins a pawn.} 10. Nxd5 Bxb5 $2 11. Nc7+ $18) 10. Na2 {
[%csl Ra6,Ra7,Rc6,Rd5][%cal Ga2b4]} Kd6 ({The attempt to cause a pawn exchange
on the queenside by} 10... a6 $2 {does not work, because the "b6" pawn becomes
too weak. This is how White can win the pawn:} 11. bxa6 Bxa6 12. Nc3 Bb7 (12...
Bc4 $2 {also doesn't work, because of} 13. e4 {[%csl Rc4,Rd5][%cal Re4d5]}) 13.
Na4 $18) 11. Nb4 Ke6 $6 {White methodically enhances his position, while the
opponent continues to follow his strategy, to wait. Now, that all white pieces
took the best positions, it is the time for the pawn attack on the kingside.} (
{Again, Black had to choose to play active:} 11... h5 $1 {[%csl Gg4]}) (11...
f6 12. g4) 12. g4 $1 {Diagram [#] The attack begins! After this move, Black's
position is hardly defensible. It does not matter in which way Black decides
to place the pawns on the kingside; this will inevitably cause a new weakness
for him. It is interesting to follow how Belavenets carried out or plan.} f5
13. g5 $1 {[%csl Rb7,Rg6,Rh7][%cal Gh2h6,Gb4d3,Gd3e5,Ge5g6] Just like this!
Now remains that the "h" pawn reaches "h6", after that the sacrifice of the
knight on "g6" is inevitable.} Kd6 14. h3 $1 {The exclamation mark for this
move is purely symbolic. As we repeatedly see, the great Grandmasters never
rush, when the opponent is totally deprived of any counterplay. Remember this
way of playing in the endgames.} Ke6 15. Na2 $1 {[%csl Gh5][%cal Ga2c3,Gc3e2,
Ge2g3,Gh3h4,Gh4h5,Gh5h6,Gg3h5] Diagram [#] The knight seeks to go on "g3" in
order to support the movement of the "h" pawn.} Kd6 16. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3e2,Ge2g3,
Gh3h4,Gh4h5]} Ke6 17. h4 Kd6 18. Ne2 Bc8 19. Ng3 Bd7 20. a4 Ke6 21. h5 Be8 22.
h6 $1 {[%csl Rg6,Rh7]} Kd6 23. Ne2 $1 {Diagram  [#] Picturesque position!
Rauzer gave up because he is completely defenceless against White's threats.
This is how the game could have continued:} Bf7 24. Nc1 Be8 25. Nd3 Bf7 26. Nb4
Be6 27. Nc6 $1 a5 28. bxa6 Kxc6 29. a7 Kb7 30. a8=Q+ Kxa8 31. Ke5 $1 {[%csl
Rh7][%cal Ge5f6,Gf6g7,Gg7h7,Gh7g7] followed by pushing the pawn on "h7" and
winning the game.} 1-0

[Event "Morelia/Linares 24th"]
[Site "Morelia/Linares"]
[Date "2007.02.25"]
[Round "7"]
[White "Ivanchuk, Vassily"]
[Black "Aronian, Levon"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "D38"]
[WhiteElo "2750"]
[BlackElo "2744"]
[Annotator "GM Grigor Grigorov"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "2r2rk1/pb1n1pp1/1p5p/2Pp4/8/P1R1PN2/1P2BPPP/R5K1 b - - 0 16"]
[PlyCount "66"]
[EventDate "2007.02.17"]
[EventRounds "14"]
[EventCountry "ESP"]
[EventCategory "20"]
[SourceVersionDate "2009.09.29"]

16... Rxc5 {Diagram [#] We already know that when we have a strong knight
against a weak bishop and the side playing with the bishop has an isolated
pawn, the defence is extremely difficult because it is almost impossible to
organize any counterplay. Let us assume that in the previous example instead
of the bishop, there has been a knight. In that case, White's advantage would
have been minimal, because there is no possibility of enhancing the pressure
on the isolated pawn. It is enough for Black to place the king on "d6" and the
knight on "e6" and the "d4" square is inaccessible for the white king.
Following, we have to must avoid remaining with a light-squared bishop when
there is an isolator on "d5". Once we have an idea of the problems created by
an isolated pawn in the endgame, I would like to grab your attention to a more
difficult and complex position of an endgame, in which there are both minor
and heavy pieces. The position in the diagram has occurred in the game between
Ivanchuk - Aronian played in 2007 in the Morelia/ Linares Tournament. Black
just played 16…R:c5 and there is an isolated pawn on the board. In this
typical position, Ivanchuk decides to play at first glance a paradoxical move:}
17. Rcc1 $5 {Diagram [#]} ({In order to understand the point behind 17.Rcc1,
we must examine the natural} 17. Rac1 {The game might follow with} Rfc8 18.
Rxc5 bxc5 19. b4 cxb4 20. Rxc8+ Bxc8 21. axb4 {Diagram [#] We have a typical
endgame with an isolated pawn. If we exclude the white light-squared bishop
and the black knight, we will have a position similar to the one in the game
between Belavenetz - Rauzer. Particularly, the presence of the knight makes
this position safe for Black. As already mentioned, Black will place the king
on "d6" and the knight on "e6". The only aim for Black is not to allow the
exchange of the knights, because in position with an isolated pawn on "d5", we
must not remain with the light-squared bishop. Taking into account these
considerations, it is clear why Ivanchuk refused to exchange the rooks on the
"c" file. Related to this issue, I would like to share one very important rule:
When playing against an isolated pawn, strive for the exchange of minor pieces.
It is recommended that the heavy artillery remains on the board. Very often,
when the heavy pieces are exchanged and the minor ones are on the board, the
side playing against the isolated pawn is losing the attacking potential.})
17... Rfc8 $6 {Black lost the opportunity to exchange the rooks and to pass
into the wanted type of position.} ({It is clear, that Black had to choose the
following variation:} 17... Rxc1+ 18. Rxc1 Rc8 19. Rxc8+ Bxc8 {with a
completely safe position.}) 18. Rd1 $1 {Diagram [#] Ivanchuk demonstrates a
great positional sense. From "d1", the rook applies frontal pressure on the
isolated pawn. The fact that Black possess the only open file is not crucial,
because White can easily control the only square for invasion ("c2")} Rc2 19.
Bb5 $1 {This is the point on which White's idea is based. Now, White has
enough time to defend the "b2" pawn and to push away the black rook from the
second horizontal.} Nf8 20. Rab1 R2c7 {Black withdrew voluntarily, without
seeing the obvious 21.Ba4.} 21. Ba4 $1 {[%cal Ga4b3] Diagram [#] White plays
logically. With the last move, the bishop seeks to go to "b3", from where it
can participate in the attack of the "d5" pawn. Please notice that it is an
endgame and we do not seek to block the pawn but to win it.} Ne6 22. Bb3 Kf8
23. h3 $1 {Diagram [#] Again the most precise continuation! With the last move,
Black placed a trap, which the Ukrainian Grandmaster avoided.} ({It looks
attractive to take the pawn through} 23. Bxd5 {, but Black has enough
counterplay for a draw.} Bxd5 24. Rxd5 Rc1+ 25. Rd1 Rxd1+ 26. Rxd1 Rc2 {
Due to the active rook, Black is out of danger.}) 23... Rc5 24. Kh2 $1 {
Diagram [#] Again a fantastic positional move. Ivanchuk prepares to double the
rooks on the "d" file, but before that does not want to allow Black to play
Rc1 with tempo. It is very important that black rooks remain on the board.} Ke7
25. Rd2 Rb5 ({If Black now tries to exchange the rooks through} 25... Rc1 {
, he will lose the central pawn without any compensation:} 26. Rxc1 Rxc1 27.
Bxd5 Bxd5 28. Rxd5 {In this position the} Rc2 {move will be met by the natural}
29. Rd2) 26. Ba2 Rbc5 27. Ne1 $1 {The black knight now is included in the
attack of the pawn. Now, the threat Nd3-b4 is very dangerous. Aronian has to
take measures.} a5 ({Trying to play actively} 27... Rc1 {does not work. White
wins the "d5" pawn after} 28. Rxc1 Rxc1 29. Nd3 Ra1 30. Nb4) 28. Rbd1 Rd8 29.
Kg3 Rb5 30. f3 $1 {Diagram [#] As every great master of the endgames, Ivanchuk
does not rush to take concrete actions. As already mentioned, the "g2" and
"f3" pawns form a structure that aims to limit the potential activity of the
black light-squared bishop. Also, it is important to take the control of the
"e4" square, wherein certain circumstances the black knight can be placed.} Rc8
$2 {Black cannot face the pressure anymore. Now, the rook on "b5" will remain
sidelined and for his rescue is necessary to sacrifice the central pawn.} ({
Probably it was better to choose solid} 30... Rc5 {, although White would have
a slight advantage. The manoeuvre Nb3-f4 is one of the interesting options
available (the readers know that our goal is to exchange minor pieces).}) 31.
Nd3 $1 {[%cal Ga3a4] Diagram [#] This natural move leads to a decisive
advantage. Now, White threatens to capture the rook by playing a3-a4} d4 32.
Bxe6 Kxe6 33. Nf4+ Ke7 34. Rxd4 Rc7 35. R1d2 {White has a completely winning
position. The rest of the game does not require any comments.} Rbc5 36. e4 Rc4
37. Rd6 R4c6 38. e5 Rc2 39. Rxc2 Rxc2 40. Rxb6 Bc6 41. b4 g5 42. Nh5 axb4 43.
axb4 Bd5 44. Ng7 Re2 45. Nf5+ Ke8 46. Nxh6 Be6 47. Rb5 Rb2 48. Rb8+ Kd7 49. Rg8
1-0

