13... Be6 {Diagram [#] I hope that the previous two examples shed enough light
on the methods of struggle against the isolated pawn in the endgame. We
already know which pieces have to be exchanged and which should remain on
board. This fundamental knowledge will help us to understand better the
middlegame positions with an isolated pawn. The last example that I would like
to share is from my own games, played in 2010 in the Open Tournament in Kavala
(Greece). Despite the modest rating of my opponent Michelakos, he performed
very well until the fifth round, when he had to play against me. Looking at
his games, I understood that when he plays a familiar variation and the
position is full of tactical resources, he could defeat a stronger player.
Considering this, I decided to play a quiet position that predict a long
manoeuvrable game, where the lack of experience and the age of my opponent
would have their say. After the opening, a typical position with an isolated
pawn arose, in which White already shaped a slight advantage. The exchange of
the dark-squared bishops and the chances for black to organize an attack on
the kingside was not real. However, the queens are still on the board, which
means that Black still has some dynamic potential. White's short-term plan
contains two main goals: 1) the blockade of the isolated pawn; 2) the exchange
of the minor pieces. In this frame of mind, White's move is absolutely logical:
} 14. Nb5 {[%cal Gb5d4] The knight seeks to go on "d4", from where is safely
block the black isolated pawn. Black does not have enough resources to control
the "d4" square. In this type of position, it is clear that the exchange of
the dark-squared bishops is only beneficial for White.} Qb6 15. Nbd4 Bg4 16. h3
Bh5 17. b3 $1 {Diagram [#] White begins to prepare for the siege of the
isolated pawn. As we already saw in the game between Ivanchuk - Aronian, the
pairing of the rooks on the "d" file is always recommended. With the last move,
White not only removes the pressure from the "b2" pawn but also prepares the
18.Qb2, followed by the pairing of the rooks. Besides that, the 17.b3 move has
another substantial advantage, now the "c4" square is under the control and
Black does not have the typical counterplay, related to Rac8, Na5 (e5)-c4.}
Rac8 18. Qb2 a6 19. Rd2 Bg6 20. Rfd1 Be4 $1 {Diagram [#] Black chooses the
most optimal places for his minor pieces. Placed on "e4", the bishop somehow
paralyses White's army. If we assume that for a moment White weakens the
control of the "d4" square, then the black bishop can be exchanged for the
knight on "f3", followed by the movement of the central pawn. Also, in some
positions, White should consider the idea or relocation of the rook on the
sixth horizontal, through the manoeuvre Rd6-g6 (look at the first article on
isolated pawn by Viktor Gavrikov). It is also an option to strengthen the
control over the "d4" square by playing Nf5 at the right moment. Because of
the thought of this character, I decided to exchange the black light-squared
bishop without losing any time.} 21. Bd3 {Offering to exchange the
light-squared bishops, White indirectly prevent the Nf5. Black faces a
difficult strategical dilemma. Black has to decide if it is safer to remain
with an isolated pawn or to pass into a position in which his pawn goes on
"e4" after the exchange of the bishops. Let us assume the second scenario.
Because it will be more distant from the black field, the "e4" pawn would be
much more difficult to protect. It will be strong in situations where space
advantage would allow Black to organize a quick attack on the kingside. In
this case, Black's problem is further complicated by the fact that White
possess the "d" open file. On the other hand, if Black chooses to play the
position with the isolated pawn, he will be doomed to the defence until the
end of the game. My opponent chose this particular continuation.} Nxd4 22. Nxd4
Qg6 $6 {The first serious inaccuracy. Black voluntarily goes to a position in
which his queen will be placed inappropriately in the centre on the board - on
"e4" it becomes an easy target for white pieces.} ({From my point of view,
Black had to choose the following continuation:} 22... Bxd3 23. Rxd3 Rc7 {
[%cal Gd8c8] with the idea Rdc8. The position now has an endgame character
that means that the blockade of the isolated pawn is not enough. White will be
forced to look for opportunities how to put more pressure on the pawn, but the
pair of the black rooks on the "c" file is ready to invade the second
horizontal, as soon as the white knight leaves the "d4" square. Another
possible development of the position includes a massive exchange of the rooks
on the "c" file, but we already know that when we play against an isolated
pawn, we avoid the exchange of heavy pieces. Maybe White should look forward
to putting gradually pressure through R3d2, Ne2, Nf4 and so on. Even in this
case, the lack of the second weakness in Black's position makes the advantage
minimal.}) 23. Bxe4 Qxe4 ({It's impossible to play} 23... dxe4 $2 {because of}
24. Nf5 $1 {[%csl Rd8,Re7][%cal Gf5e7,Rd2d8] and White is winning.}) 24. Ne2 $1
{With the last move, White begins to reorganize his forces for the attack on
the pawn. According to the position, the knight can go on "c3" as well as on
"g3" and "f4".} Rc6 {My opponent does not intend to become a passive observer
of the events and aims to create threats on the kingside. The rook is directed
to "g6" from where it predetermines the career of the white knight.} 25. Ng3
Qg6 26. Qe5 Qe6 27. Qd4 Rcd6 28. Ne2 {The manoeuvres of the white queen manage
to create coordination problems between the black pieces and my opponent can
no longer create serious threats on the kingside. Now, the knight goes to "c3",
from where it will attack the isolated pawn.} Nf5 29. Qf4 g5 $2 {Diagram [#]
Extremely serious positional mistake. With his last move, Michelakos
irreparably weakens the kingside and creates the second weakness so wanted by
me.} 30. Qg4 Qe4 31. Rd3 {Diagram [#] Important moment! Until now, I
consciously avoided the exchange of the queens, because I thought I could not
place enough pressure on the only black weakness - the isolated pawn on "d5".
After the weakening movement g7-g5, such an exchange becomes attractive,
because it is possible to create combined pressure on both weaknesses. It was
better for white for the exchange to take place on the "g4" square, because a
white pawn on "g4"would fix the weakness on "h6" and the semi-opened "h" file
is now available for the white rooks.} Qxg4 32. hxg4 Ne7 33. Nc3 f6 $6 {
A new inaccuracy. With the last move, Black blocks the connection between the
rook on "d6" and the weakened pawn on "h6". Of course, it is an understandable
desire of my opponent to centralize the king as soon as possible, which will
increase the protection of the isolated pawn. However, the isolated pawn is
not in big danger, because White cannot increase the pressure on it.} 34. g3 $1
{[%cal Gg1g2,Gf2f4,Gg2f3] White applied the golden rule of endgame - do not
rush! Before taking offensive action against the opponent's weaknesses, it is
better to occupy space and to maximum activate all pieces. White's short-term
plan includes moves as f2-f4 and Kg2-f3. Note that after the second horizontal
is released, the white rooks can be paired on the "h" file, as well as on "d"
file.} Kf7 35. Kg2 Ke6 36. f4 b6 37. Kf3 b5 {This move is inaccurate because
it unnecessarily weakens "c5" square, where the white knight could be placed.
Of course, it is not easy to defend patiently a passive position without
counterplay.} 38. Ne2 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Ge2d4,Gd3d2,Gd1h1,Gd2h2,Gh2h6] Diagram 
[#] Very important move! Before playing Rh1, I wanted to make sure that Black
does not have any counterplay related to the breakthrough d5-d4. White's
threat is Ne4, followed by placing both rooks on the "h" file.} Nc6 39. R3d2
R6d7 40. Nc1 $1 {[%csl Ra6,Rc5,Rd7,Re6][%cal Gc1d3,Gd3c5] Diagram [#] Black is
prepared to quickly include the rooks in the defence of the "h6" pawn, but now
there is a new problem - the weakness on the "c5" square and the vulnerable
pawn on "a6". The white knight is directed particularly there.} Ne7 {Black
wants to take control over the "c5" square by placing the rook on "c8", but
now "Rd7" cannot participate in the defence of the "h" pawn.} ({The move} 40...
d4 {is no longer effective, because White has a strong counter move} 41. e4 {
[%csl Rc5,Rd4][%cal Gc1d3,Rd3c5] with the blockade of the pawn. After the
knight will take the "d3" square, the "c" file will become available for the
white rooks. There are five weaknesses in Black's position - "h6", "d4", "a6",
"f5", and "c5".}) 41. Rh1 Ng8 42. Ne2 $1 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Ge2d4,Gd4f5] Diagram
[#] The black knight firmly protects the weakened pawn on "h6", but can no
longer participate in the defence of the "f5" square, to where the white
knight headed.} Rc8 43. Nd4+ Kf7 44. Nf5 Kg6 45. Rhd1 Rcd8 46. Nd4 {[%cal
Gf4f5,Gd4e6] The black pieces are really tightened. The purpose of White's
invasion is now the "e6" square. The threat is 47.Ne6 followed by the wining
of the isolated pawn. The knight on "e6" can always be supported by f4-f5.} Ne7
47. Rh1 Rd6 $2 {Diagram [#] The decisive mistake in a hopeless position. Now
follow the spectacular finale:} 48. f5+ Kh7 49. Ne6 Rc8 50. Rxh6+ {Black
resigns.} 1-0

