{[%evp 0,104,24,20,76,76,77,40,40,35,35,35,35,35,35,22,6,0,0,0,14,3,40,11,10,
10,8,8,6,-28,-24,-20,-16,-17,-17,-14,-14,-14,-21,-21,-1,-18,-17,-23,-12,-16,
-13,-24,-24,-29,-31,-31,-19,-41,-28,-29,-31,-29,-21,-26,-29,-47,-55,-50,-60,
-60,-42,-44,-38,-66,-65,-69,-73,-63,-55,-52,-51,-48,-29,-73,-54,-37,-32,-86,
-72,-63,-84,-69,-73,-55,-76,-63,-33,-55,-50,-153,-154,-161,-153,-193,-204,-253,
-250,-240,-260,-329,-380] At the beginning, I will cover White's most critical
approach against my suggested repertoire - the classical Panov Attack. The
first important crossroads arises after} 1. e4 ({For the purposes of the Slav
repertoire, our move order will be} 1. c4 c6 2. e4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5.
Nc3 Nc6 6. Nf3 {transposing to the main line}) 1... c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4.
c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Nf3 {The Panov Attack is one of the most common ways of
fighting the Caro-Kann Defence. Before the emergence of strong computer
programs, this variation was considered to be one of the critical tests for
Black. Nowadays, however, Black has found various ways to get a decent
position. While preparing the current lecture, my idea was to provide a
repertoire that is both practical and reliable. Finally, I settled for a
system that almost does not require any memorization. The understanding of the
arising middlegame positions is way more important. As I have pointed out in
the introduction, my suggested repertoire will be mainly based on the fight
against IQP.} a6 $5 {This rare move because very fashionable recently. The
idea was tested even by Grischuk. With his last move, Black takes the control
of the important b5-square. As we are going to witness on a number of
occasions, this control is crucial.} ({The traditional main line goes} 6... Bg4
7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Qb3 Bxf3 9. gxf3 e6 10. Qxb7 Nxd4 11. Bb5+ Nxb5 12. Qc6+ Ke7
13. Qxb5 Qd7 14. Nxd5+ Qxd5 15. Qxd5 exd5 {when we reach the famous Panov
Endgame Line. With a little precision, Black holds the draw here. Nevertheless,
allowing our opponent to play with a draw in the pocket is not everyone's cup
of tea.}) 7. cxd5 {This is by far the main line.} ({An important idea is to
answer} 7. Bg5 {with} Be6 {We will see this move on many occasions. Black is
planning to develop his dark-squared bishop via g7.} 8. Be2 ({After} 8. Bxf6
exf6 {[%csl Rf3,Gf6,Gf7,Gg7,Gh7][%cal Gf8b4] Black's doubled f-pawns should be
considered as a weakness. First of all, the f6-pawn is very useful at
restricting the f3-knight. Additionally, in the future, Black can consider
gaining kingside space with ...g7-g5 and ...h7-h5. Of course, our next two
moves would be ... Bb4 followed by ...0-0.}) 8... g6 {If given the chances,
Black will try to attack the centre by means of ...Bg7 followed by ...0-0 and .
..Ne4.} 9. Bxf6 exf6 10. O-O Bg7 11. Qb3 {[%csl Ba6] White is putting pressure
on b7 and d5. At this point, my suggestion would be} O-O ({Another game saw} 
11... dxc4 12. Qxb7 Na5 13. Qb4 Rb8 14. Qa3 Bf8 15. Qa4+ Bd7 16. Qc2 Bh6 {
with a balanced position. 0-1 (37) Kovalevskaya,E (2384)-Gunina,V (2431) Sochi
2020}) 12. cxd5 Na5 13. Qa3 Bxd5 14. Nxd5 Qxd5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gf6f5,Ga5c6,
Ga8d8] Black is planning to follow with ...Nc6, ...Rad8, and ...f6-f5.}) 7...
Nxd5 8. Bc4 Be6 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7,Ge8g8] Once again, we see this typical move
that prepares ... g7-g6 followed by ...Bg7.} 9. Bb3 {The most popular move.} ({
The idea behind 6. ..a6 is illustrated in the line} 9. Qb3 $2 Na5 {[%csl Ga6]
The point is that} 10. Qa4+ {can be met by} b5 {with the following sequence -}
11. Nxb5 axb5 12. Bxb5+ Bd7 $19 13. Ne5 Nc6 $1) ({After the less active} 9. Qe2
{Black can follow with} Rc8 10. Bb3 Na5 $15 {Remember this typical idea. In
all the setups based on ...g7-g6, Black wants to chase the white bishop away
from the diagonal a2-g8.}) ({To a forced draw leads} 9. Ng5 Nxc3 10. Bxe6 Nxd1
11. Bxf7+ Kd7 12. Be6+ Ke8 $11 ({Black can try to play for a win with} 12...
Kc7 {but after} 13. Bf4+ Kb6 14. Rxd1 {White has enough compensation for the
queen.})) 9... Na5 {Once again, I consider this thematic move to be Black's
most ambitious approach.} ({If you prefer to play without having to remember
absolutely nothing, your choice should be} 9... Nxc3 10. bxc3 Bxb3 11. axb3 e6
{[%csl Rb3,Rc3,Rd4][%cal Ge8g8,Gf8e7,Gb7b5,Gb5b4,Ga6a5,Ga5a4] followed by ...
Be7 and ...0-0. Later on, Black can consider ruining White's queenside
structure by playing ...b7-b5 followed by ...b5-b4 or ...a6-a5-a4. 1/2 (84)-1/
2 (84) Giri,A (2764)-Grischuk,A (2777) chess24.com INT 2020}) 10. Ng5 {[%cal
Gg5e6] Even though White is going to capture the e6-bishop, this exchange
operation is rather time-consuming. Additionally, playing against IQP, Black
is not against the exchange of pieces.} ({Another option would be} 10. Bc2 {
when the game follows with} g6 11. O-O Bg7 {[%cal Gd5c3,Ga8c8] After an
eventual exchange on c3, Black is well prepared to put pressure against the
semi-hanging pawns on c3 and d4. Therefore, White played} 12. Ne4 O-O {[%csl
Gd5][%cal Ga5c6,Gd8b6,Ga8d8,Ge6g4,Gg7d4] As I have pointed out in the
introduction, setups with ...g7-g6 are quite favourable against IQP. Besides
the possibility of putting pressure on d4, due to the g6-pawn White does not
have attacking chances. Black next move would be ...Bg4, with the idea to
exchange the defender of the d4-pawn. After that, the isolated pawn will be
under tremendous pressure.} 13. h3 {At this point, Black executed a typical
regroupment that I like very much -} Nb4 {[%csl Bg7]} 14. Bb1 Nbc6 {[%csl Rd4]
[%cal Ge6d5,Ga5c4,Gc4d6,Gd6f5,Gd5f3] In such positions, Black often tries to
put a bishop on d5, instead of a knight. The reason is that the bishop puts
indirect pressure on the f3-knight that defends the pawn. The a5-knight can be
transferred to f5 via c4-d6 route.} 15. Be3 Bd5 $15 16. Re1 Nc4 17. Bc1 Qb6 {
[%cal Ga8d8] Black enjoys a considerable advantage. His next move will be ...
Rad8. 1-0 (50) Durarbayli,V (2606)-Svane,R (2613) Chess.com INT 2021}) 10...
Qd7 11. Nxe6 Qxe6+ 12. Kf1 Nxb3 13. Qxb3 Rd8 {I consider this move to be the
most precise continuation.} ({A playable alternative is} 13... O-O-O {
Structurally speaking, Black is better but White has some dynamic
possibilities at his disposal -} 14. Qc4+ Kb8 15. Nxd5 Qxd5 16. Bf4+ Ka7 {
[%cal Ge7e6,Gf8e7,Ge7f6]} 17. Qc5+ Qxc5 18. dxc5 e6 19. Be3 Rd5 20. b4 (20. c6+
Bc5 $15) 20... Be7 {The position is roughly equal.}) 14. Nxd5 ({In the case of
} 14. Qxb7 {[%csl Bf1] Black has two options. If you want a fighting position,
I would suggest} g6 ({The move} 14... Nxc3 {leads to a draw by force after} 15.
bxc3 Qc4+ 16. Kg1 Qxc3 17. h4 Qxa1 18. Qc6+ Rd7 19. Qc8+ {with a perpetual.})
15. Bd2 Bg7 {when Black has decent compensation for the pawn.}) 14... Qxd5 15.
Qxd5 Rxd5 16. Be3 {[%csl Bd7][%cal Ba1c1,Bc1c7,Be8d7] Black is already
slightly better. He should only take care of the potential invasion on c7.} e6
17. Rc1 Kd7 18. Ke2 Bd6 {[%csl Rd4,Gd5,Rh2][%cal Gd6c7,Gc7b6,Gh7h5,Gg7g5,Gh8c8,
Gg5g4,Gh5h4,Gh4h3] Black enjoys a slight advantage that is typical for IQP
positions. In such positions, the first task of the stronger side is to
exchange one pair of rooks in order to restrict the opponent's counterplay.
The next step is to create a second weakness (that is situated far away from
the isolated pawn). In this position, the h2-pawn would be the perfect target.
Black can fix it by advancing his kingside pawns.} 19. Rhd1 h5 20. h3 h4 21.
Rc3 Rb5 22. Rc2 Rg8 23. Rd3 f6 24. a4 Rc8 25. Kd1 Ra5 26. b3 Rxc2 27. Kxc2 Rh5
28. Rc3 Rh8 29. Kd3 b5 30. axb5 axb5 31. Rc1 Ra8 32. Rc2 Ra3 33. Kc3 Ra1 34.
Rc1 Ra2 35. Rc2 Bb4+ 36. Kd3 Ra3 37. Rb2 Ra1 38. Ke4 f5+ 39. Kf4 Bc3 40. Rc2 b4
41. Bd2 Bxd2+ 42. Rxd2 Kd6 43. d5 exd5 44. Kxf5 Rb1 45. Rd3 Kc5 46. Kf4 Rb2 47.
Kf3 d4 48. g3 hxg3 49. fxg3 Kd5 50. h4 Rc2 51. Kf4 Rc3 52. Rf3 d3 {0-1 (52)
Rostgaard,T (2372)-Grandelius,N (2651) Ballerup 2020} *

