{[%evp 0,34,23,31,70,76,76,40,40,3,22,35,35,3,17,-2,18,0,6,6,6,-9,7,0,41,41,41,
28,31,18,6,-4,-4,-6,-6,-6,-6]} 1. e4 ({Once again, I remind you that the Slav
move order is} 1. c4 c6 2. e4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5) 1...
c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 {This aggressive move
requires some concrete knowledge. White develops a piece and puts pressure on
d5. Even though Black is theoretically fine everywhere, in most of the lines
some memorization is required. True to my approach for this lecture, I will
suggest a line that requires minimum concrete knowledge.} dxc4 {Black
immediately goes for a position with IQP. Another option to get such a
position is 6...e6 and only later take on c4. This move order, however, allows
White to play c4-c5 in many lines.} 7. Bxc4 {This is by far the most popular
move.} ({An important alternative is} 7. d5 Ne5 {Of course, Black cannot keep
the pawn for a long time. In order to regain it, however, White will need to
part with one of his bishops.} 8. Qd4 {[%csl Bg5]} ({Less ambitious is} 8. Bxc4
Nxc4 9. Qa4+ Bd7 10. Qxc4 h6 11. Bxf6 ({In a case of} 11. Be3 e6 12. dxe6 Bxe6
{Black has no problems whatsoever.}) ({Another high-profile game saw} 11. Bh4
g5 12. Bg3 Bg7 13. Nf3 Rc8 $132 {[%emt 0:00:01] Black's bishop pair, as well
as the vulnerable d5-pawn, provide good compensation for the slightly weakened
kingside. 0-1 (53) Gashimov,V (2733) -Ponomariov,R (2744)/Warsaw 20/Mega2011
Update}) 11... exf6 $132 {[%csl Gd6,Gd7][%cal Gf6f5,Gf8d6,Ge8g8] I like this
structure with doubled pawns on f7 and f6. Additionally, in this position,
Black enjoys a nice pair of bishops. He is ready to proceed with ...f6-f5
followed by ...Bd6 and ...0-0.}) 8... h6 9. Bf4 {The most concrete approach to
the position.} ({After} 9. Qxe5 hxg5 10. Bxc4 {[%cal Gc3b5]} a6 $5 {[%csl Gc8,
Gg7] Black is doing fine due to the powerful bishop pair. In the future, White
will have problems facing Black's play on the dark squares.} (10... g6 11. Nb5)
) ({A very important model game featured} 9. Bh4 Ng6 10. Bg3 e5 $1 (10... e6 {
is playable as well but I find the text move to be more precise.}) 11. Bxe5
Nxe5 12. Qxe5+ Be7 {Practice and concrete analysis show that Black's lead in
the development is the most important factor for the evaluation of the
position.} 13. O-O-O ({Another recent game saw} 13. Bxc4 O-O 14. Nge2 Ng4 $1 {
[%cal Ge7f6,Gd8b6] A key move in Black's strategy. His next moves will be ...
Bf6 and ...Qb6, thus initiating play on the dark squares.} 15. Qd4 Bf6 16. Qd2
Qb6 {The initiative is very powerful. After} 17. Ne4 Bg5 18. f4 Bh4+ 19. g3 Bf5
20. gxh4 Bxe4 $19 {Black had a winning position. 1-0 (50) Vasquez Schroder, R 
(2441)-Santos Latasa,J (2575) chess24.com INT 2020}) 13... Ng4 $1 {Once again,
we see the same motif. The following sequence is pretty much forced.} 14. Qxg7
Bg5+ 15. Kb1 Bf5+ 16. Ka1 Bf6 $1 17. Re1+ Qe7 18. Qxh8+ Bxh8 19. Rxe7+ Kxe7 $17
{The dust has settled. Black's bishop pair and lead in the development provide
a big advantage. 0-1 (61) Ulibin,M (2533)-Berczes,D (2521)/ Winterthur 2009/
CBM 132 Extra}) ({Black has nothing to worry about after} 9. Be3 Nd3+ 10. Bxd3
cxd3 11. Nf3 e6 $10 {with complete equality.}) ({We never fear the structure
arising after} 9. Bxf6 exf6 {The play might continue} 10. Bxc4 Nxc4 11. Qxc4
Bd6 $11 {We have already discussed this structure. Black is doing perfectly
fine. 1/2 (15) Melia,S (2431)-Grabuzova,T (2345)/ Moscow RUS 2010/The Week in
Chess 796}) 9... Ng6 10. Bxc4 (10. Bg3 e5 {is just a transposition.}) 10...
Nxf4 11. Qxf4 {[%cal Bg7g6,Bf8g7,Be8h8,Bh8g8]} g5 {[%cal Gf8g7,Ge8g8]} ({
Another decent approach would be} 11... a6 12. Nf3 g6 {Black's flexible
structure and bishop pair compensate for White's extra space.1/2 (13)-1/2
Vaganian, R-Ehlvest,J/Riga 1995/CBM 47 (62)}) 12. Qd2 ({Black has nothing to
worry about after} 12. Bb5+ Bd7 13. Bxd7+ Qxd7 14. Qd4 Bg7 {In general, due to
the vulnerable d5-pawn, exchanges of minor pieces are favourable for Black.})
12... Bg7 13. Nf3 a6 14. O-O O-O {[%cal Gd8c7,Gc8g4,Ga8d8] I like Black's
position. A possible follow up will be ...Qc7, ...Bg4, and ...Rad8, thus
putting pressure on d5. 0-1 (71) Timofeev,A (2591) -Dreev,A (2689)/playchess.
com INT 2004/CBM 099 ext}) 7... h6 $1 {It is very important to clarify the
position of White's dark-squared bishop. Depending on the position of his
bishop, Black will decide how to develop the f8-bishop.} ({The line} 7... Qxd4
8. Qxd4 Nxd4 9. O-O-O e5 {is playable but requires a lot of memorization.}) 8.
Bh4 {With a white bishop on h4, we play ...e7-e6 followed by ...Be7, and ...
Nh5 with the idea to simplify the position.} ({A very important alternative is
} 8. Be3 {[%csl Gd6] when Black should play} e6 9. Nf3 Bd6 {In positions with
IQP, with a white bishop on e3, Black should develop his dark-squared bishop
on d6. In this way, Black not only takes the e5-square under control but also
frees the e7-square for the knight.} 10. O-O ({Another typical continuation
would be} 10. a3 O-O 11. O-O Ne7 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7]} 12. Rc1 b6 13. Re1 Bb7 {
[%cal Ge7f5] In this structure, Black often transfers his knight to f5 with
two ideas in mind: 1) put additional pressure on d4 2) rule out all Bxh6
sacrifices}) 10... O-O {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7,Gc6e7,Ge7f5] This is the basic
position. You don't need to memorize anything in order to play as Black.
Black's setup remains pretty much the same against almost everything White
does.} 11. h3 ({Another typical continuation is} 11. Qe2 b6 12. Rad1 Ne7 13.
Ne5 Bb7 14. Rd3 {This typical rook lift does not work well in positions with
Be3.} Rc8 15. Rfd1 Nf5 {The point behind Black's setup. Besides all other
important duties, the f5-knight prevents White from playing Rg3. In the game,
White made a huge mistake. After} 16. Bf4 $4 Rxc4 $19 {Black was immediately
winning. 0-1 (29) Naiditsch,A (2689)-Bareev,E (2634)/Moscow 2009/EXT 2010}) ({
Another game of Naiditsch saw} 11. Rc1 b6 12. Qa4 Bb7 13. Rfd1 {[%cal Gd4d5]
White is ready to open the centre with d4-d5. Black, however, has just enough
time to play} Ne7 14. Ne5 Ned5 15. Ba6 Bxa6 16. Qxa6 Nxc3 17. bxc3 Qc8 $11 {
with equality. 1/2 (38) Naiditsch,A (2697)-Sebag,M (2486) Brest 2018}) ({
In the case of} 11. Qd2 Ne7 {White cannot sacrifice on h6 since both knights
are pretty close to the king.} 12. Rad1 a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Planning to
expand with ...b7-b5 followed by ...Bb7.} 13. Bd3 Nf5 $1 {Once again, we see
this typical idea that protects Black from all ideas based on Bxh6. After} 14.
Bf4 b5 15. Ne4 Bxf4 16. Qxf4 Bb7 17. Nxf6+ Qxf6 18. Bxf5 Qxf5 19. Qxf5 exf5 {
Black managed to achieve comfortable equality in the game 1/2 (30) Kamsky, G  
(2740)-Eljanov,P (2678) Moscow 2013}) 11... b6 12. Rc1 Bb7 {[%csl Bd6] Once
again, Black opts for the same setup. At this point, I would like to mention
that the thematic response to} 13. d5 $6 {is} Na5 {[%csl Rd5] when the d5-pawn
is dropping.}) ({As usual, the structure arising after} 8. Bxf6 exf6 9. Nf3 Bd6
{[%cal Ge8g8,Gd8d7,Ga8d8,Gc8f5] is favourable for Black. He would get a very
easy game by means of natural moves such as ...0-0, ...Bf5, ...Qd7, and ...
Rad8. Our idea is to provoke the advance d4-d5 that would grant Black better
control of the dark squares in the centre. 1/2 (30) Svidler, P (2731)-Giri, A 
(2677)/Germany 2010/EXT 2011}) ({One of the ideas behind Black's move order  
(playing ...h7-h6 without the inclusion of ...e7-e6 and Nf3) is that} 8. Bf4 {
can be met with} Qxd4 ({After} 8... e6 9. Nf3 Bd6 {White has the option of
playing} 10. Be5 {In general, the e5-bishop might create some coordination
problems in Black's camp. Therefore, I think that Black should opt for a
structural transformation after} Bxe5 11. dxe5 Qxd1+ 12. Rxd1 Nd7 {In order
not to lose the e5-pawn, White must play} 13. Bb5 Ke7 14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. O-O Ba6
16. Rfe1 c5 17. Ne4 Bb7 18. Nfd2 Bd5 $11 {Black has nothing to worry about in
this typical structure. The strong bishop, as well as the pressure along the
b-file, provide enough compensation for the vulnerable c5-pawn.}) 9. Qxd4 Nxd4
10. O-O-O Ne6 11. Bg3 Bd7 {White's compensation for the pawn is enough for
equality. Black does not experience any problems.}) 8... e6 9. Nf3 Be7 10. O-O
O-O 11. Re1 {[%csl Bh4,Bc6]} Nh5 $5 {A very important thematic idea. After the
exchange of the dark-squared bishops, Black does not experience any problems.}
12. Bxe7 ({The best reaction to} 12. Bg3 {is} Nxg3 13. hxg3 Bf6 {when the
sequence} 14. d5 Bxc3 15. bxc3 Na5 16. Bd3 exd5 17. Bc2 Bg4 {favours Black.}) (
{The immediate} 12. d5 Bxh4 13. dxc6 Bf6 14. Ne5 Qxd1 15. Raxd1 bxc6 {does not
create any problems for Black.}) 12... Nxe7 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7,Gd8d6,Gf8d8,
Gh5f6] This is the position Black was aiming for. His next moves will be ...
Nf6, ...b6, ...Bb7, followed by ...Qd6 and ...Rd8. If White does not play
energetically, he might find himself in a worse position.} 13. Ne4 {An
ambitious approach. White centralizes his knight and prevents ...Nf6. On the
other hand, Black has now better control of the d5-square.} ({To equal
positions leads} 13. d5 exd5 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Bxd5 ({Another option is} 15.
Qxd5 Qxd5 16. Bxd5 Nf6 17. Bb3 Bd7 18. Ne5 Rae8 19. Nxd7 Nxd7 {with equality.})
15... Nf4 16. Be4 Be6 17. b3 Rb8 18. Qd4 Qxd4 19. Nxd4 Bd5 $11) ({In case of} 
13. Ne5 Nf6 14. Qd3 {, typical idea for Black would be} Bd7 {[%cal Gd7c6]
planning ...Bc6.}) 13... b6 14. Ne5 Nf4 15. Qd2 Nfd5 16. Rac1 Bb7 17. Bb5 Rc8
$132 {Black is doing fine. Despite the activity of his minor pieces, White
cannot organize a kingside attack. On the other hand, White might experience
problems with the isolated pawn in the long run.} *

