{[%evp 0,145,19,31,84,13,6,11,37,15,15,11,16,-4,-22,17,2,13,13,-15,-20,-20,45,
27,35,27,19,8,21,27,42,3,3,17,21,25,20,25,32,15,19,11,28,20,23,25,22,3,24,19,
46,40,56,15,27,22,29,17,16,16,30,0,-1,17,43,24,15,10,10,20,12,20,0,0,0,14,0,6,
23,0,8,8,0,0,0,0,17,19,16,19,42,26,36,21,41,16,16,16,16,16,16,16,69,16,16,5,29,
16,16,16,16,0,0,0,58,44,39,50,77,95,105,95,208,223,323,338,350,344,346,375,383,
384,395,395,403,404,420,417,427,437,472,472,505,506,545,545,561,467] After
covering the most important lines in the Panov Attack, it's time to deal with
some sidelines. Even though these systems are not particularly challenging,
Black should know exactly what he is doing.} 1. e4 c6 2. c4 d5 3. cxd5 cxd5 4.
exd5 Nf6 {Temporarily White enjoys an extra pawn. In the long-run, however,
Black will regain it, thus obtaining better pawn structure. In most of the
systems, I will suggest developing the kingside before taking the d5-pawn. The
first important move is} 5. Qa4+ {In this system, White tries to keep the pawn
as long as possible.} Nbd7 {Black's strategy is quite simple. He is going to
follow with ...g7-g6, ...Bg7, ...0-0 and only then he can consider regaining
hte pawn. A typical way to do so is ...a7-a6, ...b7-b5, followed by . ..Bb7
and ...Nb6. The next few moves are quite logical -} 6. Nc3 g6 7. Bc4 Bg7 8. d3
O-O 9. Nf3 a6 {I remind you that we play ...a7-a6 after castling. White should
parry the threat of ...b7-b5.} 10. Qa3 {[%csl Ga3]} ({After} 10. O-O $2 b5 11.
Bxb5 Nb6 {[%cal Ga6b5] Black is winning a piece.}) 10... b6 11. O-O Bb7 {
[%cal Gb6b5,Gd7b6] This move is renewing the threat of ...b6-b5 followed by ..
.Nb6.} 12. Re1 Re8 {This is the most important tabiya of the entire variation.
Black will now decide on his plan depending on the position of the White's
dark-squared bishop. Let's start with the obvious} 13. Be3 {By taking the
b6-square under control, White tries to discourage the idea of ...b6-b5
followed by ...Nb6. Nevertheless, Black can go for this option -} b5 14. Bb3
Nb6 {Now, White is at crossroads. In order to justify 13.Be3, the most
principled decision is} 15. Bxb6 ({With a bishop on e3, the advance} 15. d6 {
is not that effective.} Bxf3 16. dxe7 ({A game of Riazantsev saw} 16. gxf3 {
when after} exd6 17. Bf4 d5 18. Rxe8+ Qxe8 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Ge8e6] Black was
already better due to White's vulnerable king. The next move will be ...Qe6.
0-1 (34) Panarin,M (2523)-Riazantsev,A (2710) Sochi 2012 CBM 148 [5.Qa4 - 13.
Be3]}) 16... Rxe7 17. gxf3 Nbd7 $132 {[%cal Gd7e5] White's vulnerable king and
inferior pawn structure give Black more than enough compensation for the pawn.}
) 15... Qxb6 16. Qb4 {Preventing the threat of ...b5-b4.} ({Of course, after} 
16. Rxe7 $4 b4 $19 {Black is winning on the spot.}) 16... Qd6 {I like this
typical move. After the exchange of the queens, Black gets a pleasant endgame.
The bishop pair as well as the better pawn structure provide more than enough
compensation for the pawn.} ({Another very decent move is} 16... Qd8 {Black
simply wants to regain the pawn. This continuation was tested by Grischuk.} 17.
a4 {This move marks the beginning of a forced sequence.} ({After} 17. Rac1 Rc8
18. Ne5 Qd6 19. Qxd6 exd6 20. Nc6 Bxc6 21. dxc6 Rxc6 $11 {The position is
equal.}) 17... Nxd5 18. Bxd5 Bxd5 19. axb5 axb5 20. Qxb5 Bxf3 21. gxf3 Rb8 22.
Qc6 Rxb2 $15 {Black was better in the game 0-1 (36) Bortnyk,O (2579)-Grischuk,
A (2747) ICC INT 2016 CBM 172 Extra}) 17. Qxd6 exd6 $44 {[%cal Gf6d7,Gd7b6,
Gd7c5,Gb5b4,Ga6a5,Ga5a4] In this endgame, White should play precisely in order
not to find himself in a difficult position. After transferring the knight to
c5 or b6, Black can consider advancing his queenside pawns. The unopposed
g7-bishop is very powerful in this position.} 18. a3 ({Nothing changes} 18.
Rxe8+ Rxe8 19. a3 Kf8 {1/2 (42)-1/2 (42) Sychev,K (2572)-Bryakin,M (2464)
Moscow 2021 CB12_2021 [5. Qa4 - 13.Be3]}) 18... Kf8 {[%cal Ge8b8,Gb7c8,Gc8d7,
Gb5b4] After a2-a3, Black's best idea is to prepare the advance ...b5-b4. The
idea of the last move is to cover the e7-square. Afterwards, Black can proceed
with ...Reb8 followd by ...Bc8-d7, and ...b5-b4.} 19. d4 (19. Rxe8+ Rxe8) 19...
Bh6 (19... Red8 $5 {[%cal Ga8b8,Gb7c8,Gb5b4]}) 20. Kf1 Rac8 (20... Reb8 $15 {
[%cal Ga6a5,Gb7a6]}) 21. h3 Rxe1+ 22. Rxe1 Re8 23. Rd1 Ke7 (23... Rb8 $1) 24.
g4 Bg7 25. Re1+ Kd8 26. Rxe8+ Kxe8 27. Ke2 Ke7 28. Kd3 Ne8 29. Nd2 Nc7 30. f3
Bc8 31. Nf1 f5 32. Ne3 Bh6 33. gxf5 gxf5 34. h4 Bd7 35. Ne2 Kf6 36. Ng2 Be8 37.
Ngf4 Bf7 38. Ba2 Ke7 39. b4 Kf6 40. Bb3 Ke7 41. Kc2 Kf6 42. Kd1 Ke7 43. Ke1 Kf6
44. Kf2 Ke7 45. Kg3 Kf6 46. Nc3 Ke7 47. Bc2 Kf6 48. Bd3 Bf8 49. Bb1 Bh6 50. Ba2
Bf8 51. Bb3 Bh6 52. Bd1 Bf8 53. Be2 Bh6 54. Bd3 Bf8 55. a4 bxa4 56. Nxa4 Nxd5
57. Nxd5+ Bxd5 58. Bxa6 Bh6 59. Nc3 Ba8 60. f4 Ke6 61. Bc8+ Kf6 62. b5 Ke7 63.
b6 Bg7 64. Ne2 Kd8 65. b7 Bxb7 66. Bxb7 Ke7 67. Bc8 Kf6 68. Kf3 Kg6 69. d5 Kf6
70. Ng3 Kg6 71. Bxf5+ Kf7 72. Bxh7 Bf6 73. Be4 {1-0 (73) Bortnyk,O (2598)
-Vazquez,G (2527) Lichess.org INT 2021 LCB18_2021 [5. Qa4 - 13.Be3]} *

