3. exd5 cxd5 4. cxd5 Nf6 5. Qa4+ Nbd7 6. Nc3 g6 7. Bc4 Bg7 8. d3 O-O 9. Nf3 a6
10. Qa3 b6 11. O-O Bb7 12. Re1 Re8 13. Bf4 {White keeps the e-file open for
the rook and makes the advance ...d5-d6 possible in many variations. Another
very thematic idea for White is the manoeuvre Ng5-e4. In my opinion, Black's
most precise move is} Rc8 $1 {By putting pressure on the c4-bishop, Black is
fighting against the manoeuvre Ng5-e4. With a rook on c8, after ...Nxe4, White
will not be able to recapture with the pawn. Since the rook controls the
c5-square as well, another good idea for Black is ...b6-b5 followed by ...Nc5.}
14. Rad1 ({A mistake would be} 14. Nd4 $2 {when after} b5 15. Bb3 Qb6 {Black
is already clearly better. A game of Riazantsev saw} 16. Qb4 $4 {when after} a5
17. Qxb5 Qxd4 $19 {Black was winning.}) ({The most principled continuation is} 
14. d6 {when Black should play} e6 {[%csl Rc4,Rd6][%cal Gf6h5,Gd7c5,Gb6b5]
White cannot support the d6-pawn for a long time due to the unstable position
of his bishops. Black's thematic ideas are ...Nh5 and ...Nc5 with or without ..
.b6-b5.} ({With a bishop on f4, the move} 14... Bxf3 $2 {is met by} 15. dxe7
$18 {[%csl Rd8,Be3,Gf4]}) 15. Bb3 Nc5 16. Rad1 Nh5 17. Bg3 Nxg3 18. hxg3 Nxb3
19. Qxb3 Qxd6 $17 {Black is clearly better. He has a better pawn structure and
strong bishop pair. 1/2 (60)-1/2 (60) Serner,A (2507)-Rydholm,L (2525) ICCF
email 2009 Corr 2013 [5.Qa4 - 13.Bf4]}) 14... b5 15. Bb3 Nc5 $17 {Without the
move ...Rc8, this knight jump would have been impossible. Now, Black will
regain the d5-pawn with comfort. He is already better and won a model game.}
16. Be5 Nxb3 17. Qxb3 Nxd5 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Ne4 Nf4 20. d4 Qd5 21. Qe3 Qxe4
22. Qxe4 Bxe4 23. Rxe4 Nd5 24. Re2 {[%csl Gd5]} f6 $1 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gg7f7,
Gg6g5,Gh7h5,Gg5g4,Gc8c4,Ge8c8,Gc4c2]} 25. g3 Rc4 26. Kf1 Kf7 27. Ne1 Rec8 28.
