{[%evp 0,30,15,25,69,20,20,12,12,16,16,-18,-1,7,-8,0,-14,-11,1,1,7,8,7,0,8,9,
21,3,26,-1,-1,4,1]} 1. e4 c6 2. c4 d5 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. exd5 Nf6 5. Bb5+ {
In this and the next chapter, we analyze White's check on move 5. His idea is
to force one of the Black pieces to d7, which blocks the queen, so it becomes
more difficult to retrieve the d5-pawn. I feel like this check only helps
Black because in many positions our knight aims to reach d5-square via b6. So,
Black should be patient and try to win back d5-pawn gradually, rather than
immediately.} Nbd7 6. Nc3 (6. Nf3 {This move is a bit tricky. We should make
sure to insert} a6 $1 {before taking on d5, so that we can break the pin and
secure the knight's position in the centre, as Wojtaszek did in the following
game:} 7. Ba4 b5 8. Bb3 Bb7 9. O-O Nxd5 10. d4 e6 $15 {Black had a very
comfortable position in the game Artemiev,V - Wojtaszek,R 2015.}) 6... a6 $5 {
White can hardly pose any problems by giving up the bishop pair with In the
same spirit as in 6.Nf3 variation.} 7. Bxd7+ {[%cal Bd8d7,Bc8d7]} (7. Ba4 {
is similar to 6.Nf3, giving Black a good position after:} b5 8. Bb3 Bb7 9. Nf3
b4 10. Na4 {after both ...Nd5 or ...Bd5 Black has comfortable play.}) 7... Qxd7
{[%cal Bb7b5,Bc8b7]} 8. Nf3 (8. Qb3 $6 {he would lose the right to castle after
} Qg4 $1 9. Kf1 b5 {and Black would have compensation, at least.} 10. Nf3 e6 $1
{Black is inviting opening of the centre.} (10... Bb7 11. d4 {when one
possible variation is:} Qf5 $146 12. Ne5 Rd8 13. a4 Ne4 14. Nxe4 Bxd5 15. Ng3
Qxe5 16. Qxb5+ axb5 17. dxe5 bxa4 18. Rxa4 e6 {and Black has enough
compensation for the pawn.}) 11. d4 Be7 $5 $146 {Black will castle and assert
his dominance on the light squares, so he should definitely have the upper
hand.}) 8... Nxd5 9. O-O {This is the best move order.} (9. d4 {allows} Qe6+ $1
10. Ne2 g6 {and only Black can be better.}) 9... b5 (9... f6 $5 {[%csl Bf7] is
a typical idea, clearing safe f7-square for the king while preventing moves
like Nf3-e5.} 10. Qb3 e6 11. Re1 Kf7 12. d3 b5 {and Black should be OK.
Personally, I would prefer to play 9...b5.}) 10. Ne5 Nxc3 {This is an
important inclusion.} 11. dxc3 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 f6 13. Nc6 Bd7 14. Na5 e5 15. Be3
Be7 {and Black has no problems in the arising endgame as he moves his bishop
to e6, king to f7, and connects his rooks.} 16. Nb7 Rb8 17. Nd6+ Bxd6 18. Rxd6
Ra8 19. f3 h5 20. Bc5 Rc8 21. Rad1 Bf5 22. Bb4 Ra8 23. Ba5 Kf7 24. Kf2 Rhc8 25.
Ke3 Re8 26. b3 Re6 27. Rxe6 Bxe6 28. Rd6 Ra7 29. Rc6 Ra8 30. Rc7+ Kg6 31. h4
Rc8 32. Ra7 Rc6 33. Bb4 f5 34. f4 exf4+ 35. Kxf4 Bf7 36. g3 Re6 37. Bc5 Be8 38.
Bd4 Bf7 39. Be5 Rc6 40. Ke3 Re6 41. Kd4 Rc6 42. Rb7 Re6 43. c4 bxc4 44. bxc4
Rc6 45. c5 a5 46. Rb6 {1-0 (46) Dgebuadze,A (2521)-Hacker,J (2073) Deizisau
2013} *

