{[%evp 0,30,31,39,74,37,20,29,35,15,24,-5,3,3,11,-8,-8,0,1,1,1,10,31,-17,9,1,
11,-9,-4,-3,-11,0,-8]} 1. e4 c6 2. c4 d5 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. exd5 Nf6 5. Bb5+ {
In this and next chapter we analyze White's check on move 5. His idea is to
force one of Black pieces to d7, which blocks the queen, so it becomes more
difficult to retrieve the d5-pawn. I feel like this check only helps Black,
because in many positions our knight aims to reach d5-square via b6. So, Black
should be patient and try to win back d5-pawn gradually, rather than
immediately.} Nbd7 6. Nc3 a6 $5 {In the same spirit as in 6.Nf3 variation.} 7.
Qa4 {This is the most testing move, keeping the pin.} g6 {[%csl Bd5][%cal
Bf8g7,Be8g8] Another reasonable option is 7...Rb8. The text move seems less
time-consuming.} (7... Rb8 8. Bxd7+ Qxd7 9. Qxd7+ Bxd7 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gb8d8,
Gd7f5] is another possibility.}) 8. Nf3 Bg7 9. O-O O-O {[%cal Gd7b6] Now White
has to do something with his bishop on b5.} 10. Bxd7 (10. Be2 Nb6 11. Qh4 Nbxd5
{It becomes obvious that White has lost too much time with his queen and
bishop. Black should be simply better after} 12. d4 Bf5 $15 {[%csl Gd5,Gf5]
with easy play.}) 10... Nxd7 {[%csl Bc8][%cal Bb7b5,Bc8b7,Bd7b6,Bb6d5,Bd7f6,
Bf6d5] because it keeps the most tension in the position. The plan is to
recoup the pawn with b5, Nb6, Bb7, etc.} 11. Qh4 {White avoids the tempo on
the queen, though this has cost him some more time. Black gets his pawn back
with} (11. d4 b5 12. Qb3 Nb6 13. Re1 (13. a4 bxa4 14. Nxa4 Nxd5 15. Nc5 Qd6 16.
Re1 Rb8 17. Qc2 Nb4 18. Qe4 Qd5 (18... e5 $5) 19. Bf4 Qxe4 20. Rxe4 Rb6 21. Bc7
Rb5 22. Be5 f6 23. Bg3 e5 24. h3 Bf5 25. Re2 exd4 26. Bd6 d3 27. Nxd3 Bxd3 28.
Rd2 Bh6 29. Bxb4 Bxd2 30. Bxf8 Kxf8 31. Ra3 Rxb2 32. Rxd3 Bb4 33. Rd7 Bc5 34.
Rxh7 a5 35. Rh8+ Kf7 36. Ra8 Ra2 37. Kh2 a4 38. Ne1 Bd6+ 39. g3 Rxf2+ 40. Kg1
Ra2 41. g4 Bc5+ 42. Kf1 Rf2+ 43. Kg1 Rd2+ 44. Kf1 a3 {0-1 (44) Miezis,N (2435)
-Oll,L (2610) Riga 1995}) 13... Bb7 14. Bg5 Re8 15. Rad1 (15. a4 Bxd5 16. Nxd5
Qxd5 17. Qxd5 Nxd5 18. axb5 f6 19. Bd2 axb5 $15) 15... Nxd5 16. Ne4 {[%csl Bd5]
[%cal Bb7d5]} Qb6 (16... Nb6 {[%cal Gb7d5]} 17. Nc5 Bd5 {[%cal Bb6c4,Bc4d6,
Bd6f5,Bf7f6]} 18. Qd3 Nc4 19. Bc1 Qb6 20. b3 Nd6 $17 {[%cal Ga8d8,Gd6f5]}) 17.
Bh4 a5 18. Ne5 a4 19. Qg3 Nf6 20. Nc5 Bd5 21. a3 Rad8 22. Qc3 Ba8 23. f3 Nd5
24. Qc1 Qa7 25. Bf2 Nb6 26. h4 Bd5 27. Qf4 Nc4 28. Ned3 Qb8 29. Qc1 Na5 30. Qc3
Nc4 31. Qc1 Qa7 32. h5 Na5 33. Qf4 Qb8 34. hxg6 hxg6 35. Qh4 Bf6 36. Qh6 Bg7
37. Qe3 Nc4 38. Qc1 Qa7 39. Ne5 Rc8 40. Ned3 Red8 41. Qf4 Qc7 42. Qg5 Bf6 43.
Qh6 Bg7 44. Qg5 {1/2-1/2 (44) Miezis,N (2525)-Heinbuch,D (2383) Bad
Woerishofen 1999}) 11... Nf6 12. d4 Nxd5 13. Bh6 (13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14. Bh6 {
it is very important to play} f6 $5 $146 {which limits the mobility of white
knight. After} 15. Rfe1 Re8 {[%csl Gc8] Black should enjoy a slight advantage
thanks to his light-squared bishop and isolated d-pawn.}) 13... Bf6 $5 $146 {
This new move might be an improvement. It surely keeps more tension in the
position.} 14. Qe4 (14. Ng5 Re8 $17 {[%csl Rd4,Bg5,Bh6][%cal Gc8f5,Gd5c3,Gd8d5]
In fact, White pieces look stuck on the kingside.}) (14. Bg5 Be6 $1 {and Black
seems to be slightly better thanks to strong control of the square in front of
the isolated pawn.}) 14... Nxc3 15. bxc3 Re8 {[%csl Rc3,Rd4][%cal Gc8e6] with
a slight positional advantage in the view of blockade of White's hanging pawn
pair after Be6, b5, Rc8, etc.} *

