{[%evp 0,34,19,31,68,30,30,8,50,35,24,-15,11,17,21,5,12,5,3,18,12,9,9,4,12,9,
10,-1,11,20,30,16,8,17,36,36,29]} 1. e4 c6 2. c4 {This position also can arise
from different move order: 1. c4-c6 2.e4. So if you are a Slav player yourself,
this analysis will be helpful to you when it comes to the English opening (1.
c4).} d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. cxd5 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nxd5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Bb5 {White
postpones d2-d4, preferring quick development. These sidelines are not too
dangerous, though, and there is also not too much to memorize compared to most
other Caro Kann variations.} (7. Bc4 {is similar, but once again, not a
challenging line.} Nb6 8. Bb3 (8. Bb5 g6 9. d4 Bg7 10. O-O O-O {is similar to
8.Bb3. Black is doing very well here.}) 8... Na5 {This is a rare move with the
idea of going . ..g6.} (8... g6 9. a4 $1 Na5 10. Ba2 {can be problematic.}) 9.
Bc2 (9. O-O Nxb3 10. Qxb3 {This approach by White has more drawbacks than
advantages. Black will have a bishop pair against the isolated pawn, so only
he can be better. Several good plans are possible, such as ...Be6 with the
idea of going ...g6, or simply ... e6.}) 9... g6 $146 {This new move makes a
lot of sense considering that White plans to put the pawn on d4.} 10. d4 Bg7
11. O-O O-O {and this looks like a very good Gruenfeld type of position for
Black.}) (7. d4 {transposes to the main line of the Panov attack after:} g6 (
7... a6 8. Bc4 Be6)) 7... g6 $5 {This is an interesting sideline. Black does
not mind giving a pawn to speed up his development and put his bishop pair to
work.} 8. Qa4 (8. Ne5 {is another way to take advantage of the pin.} Nxc3 $5
$146 {A new move, though not the only good move in the position.} (8... Qd6 {
is simple and good. For example:} 9. d4 (9. Nc4 $146 Qc5 10. Qf3 Nxc3 11. Bxc6+
Qxc6 12. Qxc6+ bxc6 13. dxc3 h5 $5 {and Black is okay in the endgame thanks to
his bishop pair.}) 9... Bg7 10. O-O O-O 11. Ne4 Qc7 {and Black has no problems.
It is good to have a fianchettoed bishop against the isolated pawn.}) 9. dxc3
Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1 a6 $1 {This was the idea of 8.. .Nc3!?N} 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 {
Black's pawn structure is not ideal, but the bishop pair compensates for this,
so we can consider this position balanced.}) (8. Qb3 {is another move that has
to be considered. Black gets very good play with an unexpected resource:} Be6
$5 9. Nd4 Qd7 10. Nxe6 Qxe6+ 11. Kf1 O-O-O $15 {The king on f1 is a problem
for White, while Black has castled, so we should give him an edge.}) 8... Nb6 (
8... Bg7 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. Qxc6+) 9. Bxc6+ (9. Qf4 $6 {looks inconsequent.
Black can sacrifice the pawn for development with:} Bg7 10. Ne5 $6 O-O 11. Nxc6
bxc6 12. Bxc6 {and after the new move} Ba6 $1 $146 {White's king is stuck in
the centre, giving Black a great initiative, even worth sacrificing the
exchange.} 13. Bxa8 $2 Qxa8 {White will get destroyed on the light squares.}
14. d3 Bxd3 15. Qf3 Bxc3+ $1 16. bxc3 Be4 17. Qf4 Bxg2 $19) (9. Qh4 {is quite
harmless. Black has two good continuations:} Bg7 (9... e6 $5 $146 {After this
move, White is more or less forced to exchange queens, which leads to a
balanced endgame.} 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. d4 f6 $5 {covering e5- and g5-squares
and preparing to bring the king to the safe square f7.}) 10. d4 O-O 11. Bxc6 {
White's idea with this exchange is to create an isolated pawn for Black, so
that he has a target, as well.} bxc6 12. O-O (12. Bh6 {Here I would suggest} e6
$5 $146 13. Qxd8 Rxd8 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. O-O Ba6 16. Rfe1 Nd5 {The endgame is
balanced as isolated pawns offset each other. Likewise, outposts c5 for White
and d5 for Black are equally important.} 17. Ne4 Nf4 18. Nc5 Bc4) 12... e5 $5
$146 13. Qxd8 Rxd8 14. Nxe5 (14. dxe5 Bg4 15. Re1 Re8 {Black will soon return
the sacrificed pawn with approximate equality.}) 14... Rxd4 15. Nxc6 Rd3 {
Black has full compensation for the pawn in an open position with bishop pair.}
) 9... bxc6 10. Qxc6+ Bd7 11. Qe4 Bg7 {For the sacrificed pawn, Black gets a
lead in development and open diagonals for his bishops.} 12. O-O (12. d4 Rc8
13. O-O {transposes to 12.0-0}) 12... Rc8 13. d4 (13. Qe2 Bc6 $5 $146 {This
contains a little nuance. Now White can not push d4 easily anymore.} (13... O-O
14. d4 Be6 $5 $146 {Black will play ...Nd5 next and will have compensation for
the pawn.}) 14. Ne5 (14. d4 {transposes to 13.d4} Bxf3 15. Qxf3 Qxd4 16. Be3
Qf6 $5 $146 17. Qxf6 Bxf6 18. a4 Bxc3 $5 19. bxc3 Rc7 20. Rfb1 Kd7 $5 21. Bxb6
axb6 22. Rxb6 Rxc3) 14... O-O {White has little choice now. His development
would suffer if he wouldn't continue} 15. d4 Qxd4 16. Nxc6 Rxc6 17. Qxe7 a5 {
and it is obvious that Black has enough compensation for the pawn thanks to
all his active pieces.}) (13. Re1 Bc6 14. Qe2 O-O 15. Ne5 Ba8 16. d3 Nd5 $15 {
when Black definitely has compensation for the pawn, but he may even play for
an edge in the long run, thanks to his positional trumps.}) 13... Bc6 14. Qe2
Bxf3 {The simplest if we are after equality.} (14... O-O {rather provides
long-term compensation by keeping more pieces on the board.}) 15. Qxf3 Qxd4 16.
Bg5 (16. Be3 {was analyzed in 13.Qe2 line.}) 16... h6 17. Be3 Qf6 $5 $146 {
This leads to forced equality, similar to 13.Qe2 variation.} *

